98  /*************************************************************************
99  Dense solver for A*x=b with N*N real matrix A and N*1 real vectorx x and
100  b. This is "slow-but-feature rich" version of the linear solver. Faster
101  version is RMatrixSolveFast() function.
102 
103  Algorithm features:
104  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
105  * condition number estimation
106  * iterative refinement
107  * O(N^3) complexity
108 
109  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
110  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system
111  ! and performs iterative refinement, which results in
112  ! significant performance penalty when compared with "fast"
113  ! version which just performs LU decomposition and calls
114  ! triangular solver.
115  !
116  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
117  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
118  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
119  ! calculations. It is also very significant on small matrices.
120  !
121  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
122  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
123  ! you to use faster solver, RMatrixSolveFast() function.
124 
125  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
126  !
127  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
128  ! of this function:
129  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
130  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
131  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
132  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
133  !
134  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
135  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
136  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
137 
138  INPUT PARAMETERS
139  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
140  N - size of A
141  B - array[0..N-1], right part
142 
143  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
144  Info - return code:
145  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
146  * -1 N<=0 was passed
147  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
148  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
149  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
150  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
151  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
152  X - array[N], it contains:
153  * info>0 => solution
154  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
155 
156  -- ALGLIB --
157  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
158  *************************************************************************/

387  /*************************************************************************
388  Dense solver.
389 
390  This subroutine solves a system A*x=b, where A is NxN non-denegerate
391  real matrix given by its LU decomposition, x and b are real vectors. This
392  is "slow-but-robust" version of the linear LU-based solver. Faster version
393  is RMatrixLUSolveFast() function.
394 
395  Algorithm features:
396  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
397  * O(N^2) complexity
398  * condition number estimation
399 
400  No iterative refinement is provided because exact form of original matrix
401  is not known to subroutine. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
402  need iterative refinement.
403 
404  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
405  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
406  ! which results in 10-15x performance penalty when compared
407  ! with "fast" version which just calls triangular solver.
408  !
409  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
410  ! cost of large LU decomposition. However, if you call this
411  ! function many times for the same left side, this overhead
412  ! BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant for small-
413  ! scale problems.
414  !
415  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
416  ! RMatrixLUSolveFast() function.
417 
418  INPUT PARAMETERS
419  LUA - array[N,N], LU decomposition, RMatrixLU result
420  P - array[N], pivots array, RMatrixLU result
421  N - size of A
422  B - array[N], right part
423 
424  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
425  Info - return code:
426  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
427  * -1 N<=0 was passed
428  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
429  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
430  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
431  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
432  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
433  X - array[N], it contains:
434  * info>0 => solution
435  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
436 
437 
438  -- ALGLIB --
439  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
440  *************************************************************************/

501  /*************************************************************************
502  Dense solver.
503 
504  Similar to RMatrixLUSolve() but solves task with multiple right parts
505  (where b and x are NxM matrices). This is "robust-but-slow" version of
506  LU-based solver which performs additional checks for non-degeneracy of

508  "fast-without-any-checks" version, RMatrixLUSolveMFast().
509 
510  Algorithm features:
511  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
512  * O(M*N^2) complexity
513  * condition number estimation
514 
515  No iterative refinement is provided because exact form of original matrix
516  is not known to subroutine. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
517  need iterative refinement.
518

520  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
521  ! which results in significant performance penalty when
522  ! compared with "fast" version which just calls triangular
523  ! solver.
524  !
525  ! This performance penalty is especially apparent when you use
526  ! ALGLIB parallel capabilities (condition number estimation is
527  ! inherently sequential). It also becomes significant for
528  ! small-scale problems.
529  !
530  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,

645  /*************************************************************************
646  Dense solver.
647 
648  This subroutine solves a system A*x=b, where BOTH ORIGINAL A AND ITS
649  LU DECOMPOSITION ARE KNOWN. You can use it if for some reasons you have
650  both A and its LU decomposition.
651 
652  Algorithm features:
653  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
654  * condition number estimation
655  * iterative refinement
656  * O(N^2) complexity
657 
658  INPUT PARAMETERS
659  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
660  LUA - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], LU decomposition, RMatrixLU result
661  P - array[0..N-1], pivots array, RMatrixLU result
662  N - size of A
663  B - array[0..N-1], right part
664 
665  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
666  Info - return code:
667  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
668  * -1 N<=0 was passed
669  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
670  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
671  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
672  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
673  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
674  X - array[N], it contains:
675  * info>0 => solution
676  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
677 
678  -- ALGLIB --
679  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
680  *************************************************************************/
681  public static void rmatrixmixedsolve(double[,] a, double[,] lua, int[] p, int n, double[] b, out int info, out densesolverreport rep, out double[] x)

683  info = 0;
684  rep = new densesolverreport();
685  x = new double[0];
686  directdensesolvers.rmatrixmixedsolve(a, lua, p, n, b, ref info, rep.innerobj, ref x, null);
687  }

749  /*************************************************************************
750  Complex dense solver for A*X=B with N*N complex matrix A, N*M complex
751  matrices X and B. "Slow-but-feature-rich" version which provides
752  additional functions, at the cost of slower performance. Faster version
753  may be invoked with CMatrixSolveMFast() function.
754 
755  Algorithm features:
756  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
757  * condition number estimation
758  * iterative refinement
759  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
760 
761  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
762  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system
763  ! and performs iterative refinement, which results in
764  ! significant performance penalty when compared with "fast"
765  ! version which just performs LU decomposition and calls
766  ! triangular solver.
767  !
768  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
769  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
770  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
771  ! calculations.
772  !
773  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
774  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
775  ! you to use faster solver, CMatrixSolveMFast() function.
776 
777  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
778  !
779  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
780  ! of this function:
781  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
782  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
783  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
784  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
785  !
786  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
787  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
788  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
789 
790  INPUT PARAMETERS
791  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
792  N - size of A
793  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
794  M - right part size
795  RFS - iterative refinement switch:
796  * True - refinement is used.
797  Less performance, more precision.
798  * False - refinement is not used.
799  More performance, less precision.
800 
801  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
802  Info - return code:
803  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
804  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
805  * -1 N<=0 was passed
806  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
807  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
808  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
809  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
810  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
811  X - array[N,M], it contains:
812  * info>0 => solution
813  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
814 
815  -- ALGLIB --
816  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
817  *************************************************************************/
818  public static void cmatrixsolvem(complex[,] a, int n, complex[,] b, int m, bool rfs, out int info, out densesolverreport rep, out complex[,] x)
819  {
820  info = 0;
821  rep = new densesolverreport();
822  x = new complex[0,0];
823  directdensesolvers.cmatrixsolvem(a, n, b, m, rfs, ref info, rep.innerobj, ref x, null);
824  }

1150  /*************************************************************************
1151  Complex dense linear solver for A*x=b with complex N*N A given by its LU
1152  decomposition and N*1 vectors x and b. This is "slow-but-robust" version
1153  of the complex linear solver with additional features which add
1154  significant performance overhead. Faster version is CMatrixLUSolveFast()
1155  function.
1156 
1157  Algorithm features:
1158  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
1159  * O(N^2) complexity
1160  * condition number estimation
1161 
1162  No iterative refinement is provided because exact form of original matrix
1163  is not known to subroutine. Use CMatrixSolve or CMatrixMixedSolve if you
1164  need iterative refinement.
1165 
1166  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
1167  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
1168  ! which results in 10-15x performance penalty when compared
1169  ! with "fast" version which just calls triangular solver.
1170  !
1171  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
1172  ! cost of large LU decomposition. However, if you call this
1173  ! function many times for the same left side, this overhead
1174  ! BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant for small-
1175  ! scale problems.
1176  !
1177  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
1178  ! CMatrixLUSolveFast() function.

1180  INPUT PARAMETERS
1181  LUA - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], LU decomposition, CMatrixLU result
1182  P - array[0..N-1], pivots array, CMatrixLU result
1183  N - size of A
1184  B - array[0..N-1], right part
1185 
1186  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1187  Info - return code:
1188  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
1189  * -1 N<=0 was passed
1190  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
1191  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
1192  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
1193  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
1194  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
1195  X - array[N], it contains:
1196  * info>0 => solution
1197  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
1198 
1199  -- ALGLIB --
1200  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey

1220  decomposition and N*1 vectors x and b. This is fast lightweight version
1221  of solver, which is significantly faster than CMatrixLUSolve(), but does
1222  not provide additional information (like condition numbers).

1225  * O(N^2) complexity
1226  * no additional time-consuming features, just triangular solver
1227 
1228  INPUT PARAMETERS
1229  LUA - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], LU decomposition, CMatrixLU result
1230  P - array[0..N-1], pivots array, CMatrixLU result
1231  N - size of A
1232  B - array[0..N-1], right part
1233 
1234  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1235  Info - return code:
1236  * -3 matrix is exactly singular (ill conditioned matrices
1237  are not recognized).
1238  * -1 N<=0 was passed
1239  * 1 task is solved
1240  B - array[N]:
1241  * info>0 => overwritten by solution
1242  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
1243 
1244  NOTE: unlike CMatrixLUSolve(), this function does NOT check for
1245  near-degeneracy of input matrix. It checks for EXACT degeneracy,
1246  because this check is easy to do. However, very badly conditioned
1247  matrices may went unnoticed.
1248 
1249 
1250  -- ALGLIB --
1251  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1252  *************************************************************************/

1254  {

1256  directdensesolvers.cmatrixlusolvefast(lua, p, n, b, ref info, null);
1257  }

1362  /*************************************************************************
1363  Dense solver for A*X=B with N*N symmetric positive definite matrix A, and
1364  N*M vectors X and B. It is "slow-but-feature-rich" version of the solver.
1365 
1366  Algorithm features:
1367  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
1368  * condition number estimation
1369  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
1370  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
1371 
1372  No iterative refinement is provided because such partial representation of
1373  matrix does not allow efficient calculation of extra-precise matrix-vector
1374  products for large matrices. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
1375  need iterative refinement.
1376 
1377  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
1378  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
1379  ! which results in significant performance penalty when
1380  ! compared with "fast" version which just performs Cholesky
1381  ! decomposition and calls triangular solver.
1382  !
1383  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
1384  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
1385  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
1386  ! calculations.
1387  !
1388  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
1389  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
1390  ! you to use faster solver, SPDMatrixSolveMFast() function.
1391 
1392  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
1393  !
1394  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
1395  ! of this function:
1396  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
1397  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
1398  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
1399  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
1400  !
1401  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
1402  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
1403  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
1404 
1405  INPUT PARAMETERS
1406  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
1407  N - size of A
1408  IsUpper - what half of A is provided
1409  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
1410  M - right part size
1411 
1412  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1413  Info - return code:
1414  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or non-SPD.
1415  * -1 N<=0 was passed
1416  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
1417  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
1418  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
1419  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
1420  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
1421  X - array[N,M], it contains:
1422  * info>0 => solution
1423  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
1424 
1425  -- ALGLIB --
1426  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1427  *************************************************************************/

1632  /*************************************************************************
1633  Dense solver for A*X=B with N*N symmetric positive definite matrix A given
1634  by its Cholesky decomposition, and N*M vectors X and B. It is "slow-but-
1635  feature-rich" version of the solver which estimates condition number of
1636  the system.
1637 
1638  Algorithm features:
1639  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
1640  * O(M*N^2) complexity
1641  * condition number estimation
1642  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
1643 
1644  No iterative refinement is provided because such partial representation of
1645  matrix does not allow efficient calculation of extra-precise matrix-vector
1646  products for large matrices. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
1647  need iterative refinement.
1648 
1649  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
1650  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
1651  ! which results in significant performance penalty when
1652  ! compared with "fast" version which just calls triangular
1653  ! solver. Amount of overhead introduced depends on M (the
1654  ! larger - the more efficient).
1655  !
1656  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
1657  ! cost of large LU decomposition. However, if you call this
1658  ! function many times for the same left side, this overhead
1659  ! BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant for small-
1660  ! scale problems (N<50).
1661  !
1662  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
1663  ! SPDMatrixCholeskySolveMFast() function.
1664 
1665  INPUT PARAMETERS
1666  CHA - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], Cholesky decomposition,
1667  SPDMatrixCholesky result
1668  N - size of CHA
1669  IsUpper - what half of CHA is provided
1670  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
1671  M - right part size
1672 
1673  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1674  Info - return code:
1675  * -3 A is is exactly singular or badly conditioned
1676  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
1677  * -1 N<=0 was passed
1678  * 1 task was solved
1679  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
1680  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
1681  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
1682  X - array[N]:
1683  * for info>0 contains solution
1684  * for info=-3 filled by zeros
1685 
1686  -- ALGLIB --
1687  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1688  *************************************************************************/

1693  x = new double[0,0];

1749  /*************************************************************************
1750  Dense solver for A*x=b with N*N symmetric positive definite matrix A given
1751  by its Cholesky decomposition, and N*1 real vectors x and b. This is "slow-
1752  but-feature-rich" version of the solver which, in addition to the
1753  solution, performs condition number estimation.
1754 
1755  Algorithm features:
1756  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
1757  * O(N^2) complexity
1758  * condition number estimation
1759  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
1760 
1761  No iterative refinement is provided because such partial representation of
1762  matrix does not allow efficient calculation of extra-precise matrix-vector
1763  products for large matrices. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
1764  need iterative refinement.
1765 
1766  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
1767  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
1768  ! which results in 10-15x performance penalty when compared
1769  ! with "fast" version which just calls triangular solver.
1770  !
1771  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
1772  ! cost of large LU decomposition. However, if you call this
1773  ! function many times for the same left side, this overhead
1774  ! BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant for small-
1775  ! scale problems (N<50).
1776  !
1777  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
1778  ! SPDMatrixCholeskySolveFast() function.
1779 
1780  INPUT PARAMETERS
1781  CHA - array[N,N], Cholesky decomposition,
1782  SPDMatrixCholesky result
1783  N - size of A
1784  IsUpper - what half of CHA is provided
1785  B - array[N], right part
1786 
1787  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1788  Info - return code:
1789  * -3 A is is exactly singular or ill conditioned
1790  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
1791  * -1 N<=0 was passed
1792  * 1 task is solved
1793  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
1794  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm

1861  /*************************************************************************
1862  Dense solver for A*X=B, with N*N Hermitian positive definite matrix A and
1863  N*M complex matrices X and B. "Slow-but-feature-rich" version of the
1864  solver.
1865 
1866  Algorithm features:
1867  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
1868  * condition number estimation
1869  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
1870  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
1871 
1872  No iterative refinement is provided because such partial representation of
1873  matrix does not allow efficient calculation of extra-precise matrix-vector
1874  products for large matrices. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
1875  need iterative refinement.
1876 
1877  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
1878  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
1879  ! which results in significant performance penalty when
1880  ! compared with "fast" version which just calls triangular
1881  ! solver.
1882  !
1883  ! This performance penalty is especially apparent when you use
1884  ! ALGLIB parallel capabilities (condition number estimation is
1885  ! inherently sequential). It also becomes significant for
1886  ! small-scale problems (N<100).
1887  !
1888  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
1889  ! HPDMatrixSolveMFast() function.
1890 
1891  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
1892  !
1893  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
1894  ! of this function:
1895  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
1896  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
1897  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
1898  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
1899  !
1900  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
1901  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
1902  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
1903 
1904  INPUT PARAMETERS
1905  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
1906  N - size of A
1907  IsUpper - what half of A is provided
1908  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
1909  M - right part size

2120  /*************************************************************************
2121  Dense solver for A*X=B with N*N Hermitian positive definite matrix A given
2122  by its Cholesky decomposition and N*M complex matrices X and B. This is
2123  "slow-but-feature-rich" version of the solver which, in addition to the
2124  solution, estimates condition number of the system.
2125 
2126  Algorithm features:
2127  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
2128  * O(M*N^2) complexity
2129  * condition number estimation
2130  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
2131 
2132  No iterative refinement is provided because such partial representation of
2133  matrix does not allow efficient calculation of extra-precise matrix-vector
2134  products for large matrices. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
2135  need iterative refinement.
2136

2138  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
2139  ! which results in significant performance penalty when
2140  ! compared with "fast" version which just calls triangular
2141  ! solver. Amount of overhead introduced depends on M (the
2142  ! larger - the more efficient).
2143  !
2144  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
2145  ! cost of large Cholesky decomposition. However, if you call
2146  ! this function many times for the same left side, this
2147  ! overhead BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant
2148  ! for small-scale problems (N<50).
2149  !
2150  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
2151  ! HPDMatrixCholeskySolveMFast() function.

2155  CHA - array[N,N], Cholesky decomposition,

2159  B - array[N,M], right part
2160  M - right part size
2161 
2162  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
2163  Info - return code:
2164  * -3 A is singular, or VERY close to singular.
2165  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
2166  * -1 N<=0 was passed
2167  * 1 task was solved
2168  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
2169  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
2170  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
2171  X - array[N]:
2172  * for info>0 contains solution
2173  * for info=-3 filled by zeros

2348 
2349  /*************************************************************************
2350  Dense solver.
2351 
2352  This subroutine finds solution of the linear system A*X=B with non-square,
2353  possibly degenerate A. System is solved in the least squares sense, and
2354  general least squares solution X = X0 + CX*y which minimizes |A*X-B| is
2355  returned. If A is non-degenerate, solution in the usual sense is returned.
2356 
2357  Algorithm features:
2358  * automatic detection (and correct handling!) of degenerate cases
2359  * iterative refinement
2360  * O(N^3) complexity
2361 
2362  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
2363  !
2364  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
2365  ! of this function:
2366  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
2367  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
2368  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
2369  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
2370  !
2371  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
2372  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
2373  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
2374 
2375  INPUT PARAMETERS
2376  A - array[0..NRows-1,0..NCols-1], system matrix
2377  NRows - vertical size of A
2378  NCols - horizontal size of A
2379  B - array[0..NCols-1], right part
2380  Threshold- a number in [0,1]. Singular values beyond Threshold are
2381  considered zero. Set it to 0.0, if you don't understand
2382  what it means, so the solver will choose good value on its
2383  own.
2384 
2385  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
2386  Info - return code:
2387  * -4 SVD subroutine failed
2388  * -1 if NRows<=0 or NCols<=0 or Threshold<0 was passed
2389  * 1 if task is solved
2390  Rep - solver report, see below for more info
2391  X - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], it contains:
2392  * solution of A*X=B (even for singular A)
2393  * zeros, if SVD subroutine failed
2394 
2395  SOLVER REPORT
2396 
2397  Subroutine sets following fields of the Rep structure:
2398  * R2 reciprocal of condition number: 1/cond(A), 2-norm.
2399  * N = NCols
2400  * K dim(Null(A))
2401  * CX array[0..N-1,0..K-1], kernel of A.
2402  Columns of CX store such vectors that A*CX[i]=0.
2403 
2404  -- ALGLIB --
2405  Copyright 24.08.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
2406  *************************************************************************/
2407  public static void rmatrixsolvels(double[,] a, int nrows, int ncols, double[] b, double threshold, out int info, out densesolverlsreport rep, out double[] x)
2408  {
2409  info = 0;
2410  rep = new densesolverlsreport();
2411  x = new double[0];
2412  directdensesolvers.rmatrixsolvels(a, nrows, ncols, b, threshold, ref info, rep.innerobj, ref x, null);
2413  }
2414 
2415  public static void rmatrixsolvels(double[,] a, int nrows, int ncols, double[] b, double threshold, out int info, out densesolverlsreport rep, out double[] x, alglib.xparams _params)
2416  {
2417  info = 0;
2418  rep = new densesolverlsreport();
2419  x = new double[0];
2420  directdensesolvers.rmatrixsolvels(a, nrows, ncols, b, threshold, ref info, rep.innerobj, ref x, _params);
2421  }

2496  /*************************************************************************
2497  This function initializes linear LSQR Solver. This solver is used to solve
2498  non-symmetric (and, possibly, non-square) problems. Least squares solution
2499  is returned for non-compatible systems.
2500 
2501  USAGE:
2502  1. User initializes algorithm state with LinLSQRCreate() call
2503  2. User tunes solver parameters with LinLSQRSetCond() and other functions
2504  3. User calls LinLSQRSolveSparse() function which takes algorithm state
2505  and SparseMatrix object.
2506  4. User calls LinLSQRResults() to get solution
2507  5. Optionally, user may call LinLSQRSolveSparse() again to solve another
2508  problem with different matrix and/or right part without reinitializing
2509  LinLSQRState structure.
2510 
2511  INPUT PARAMETERS:
2512  M - number of rows in A
2513  N - number of variables, N>0
2514 
2515  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
2516  State - structure which stores algorithm state
2517 
2518  NOTE: see also linlsqrcreatebuf() for version which reuses previously
2519  allocated place as much as possible.
2520 
2521  -- ALGLIB --
2522  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
2523  *************************************************************************/

2525  {
2526  state = new linlsqrstate();
2527  linlsqr.linlsqrcreate(m, n, state.innerobj, null);
2528  }

2790  /*************************************************************************
2791  This subroutine submits request for termination of the running solver. It
2792  can be called from some other thread which wants LSQR solver to terminate
2793  (obviously, the thread running LSQR solver can not request termination
2794  because it is already busy working on LSQR).
2795 
2796  As result, solver stops at point which was "current accepted" when
2797  termination request was submitted and returns error code 8 (successful
2798  termination). Such termination is a smooth process which properly
2799  deallocates all temporaries.
2800 
2801  INPUT PARAMETERS:
2802  State - solver structure
2803 
2804  NOTE: calling this function on solver which is NOT running will have no
2805  effect.
2806 
2807  NOTE: multiple calls to this function are possible. First call is counted,
2808  subsequent calls are silently ignored.
2809 
2810  NOTE: solver clears termination flag on its start, it means that if some
2811  other thread will request termination too soon, its request will went
2812  unnoticed.
2813 
2814  -- ALGLIB --
2815  Copyright 08.10.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
2816  *************************************************************************/
2817  public static void linlsqrrequesttermination(linlsqrstate state)
2818  {
2819 
2820  linlsqr.linlsqrrequesttermination(state.innerobj, null);
2821  }
2822 
2823  public static void linlsqrrequesttermination(linlsqrstate state, alglib.xparams _params)
2824  {
2825 
2826  linlsqr.linlsqrrequesttermination(state.innerobj, _params);
2827  }

2866  /*************************************************************************
2867  Polynomial root finding.
2868 
2869  This function returns all roots of the polynomial
2870  P(x) = a0 + a1*x + a2*x^2 + ... + an*x^n
2871  Both real and complex roots are returned (see below).
2872 
2873  INPUT PARAMETERS:
2874  A - array[N+1], polynomial coefficients:
2875  * A[0] is constant term
2876  * A[N] is a coefficient of X^N
2877  N - polynomial degree
2878 
2879  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
2880  X - array of complex roots:
2881  * for isolated real root, X[I] is strictly real: IMAGE(X[I])=0
2882  * complex roots are always returned in pairs - roots occupy
2883  positions I and I+1, with:
2884  * X[I+1]=Conj(X[I])
2885  * IMAGE(X[I]) > 0
2886  * IMAGE(X[I+1]) = -IMAGE(X[I]) < 0
2887  * multiple real roots may have non-zero imaginary part due
2888  to roundoff errors. There is no reliable way to distinguish
2889  real root of multiplicity 2 from two complex roots in
2890  the presence of roundoff errors.
2891  Rep - report, additional information, following fields are set:
2892  * Rep.MaxErr - max( |P(xi)| ) for i=0..N-1. This field
2893  allows to quickly estimate "quality" of the roots being
2894  returned.
2895 
2896  NOTE: this function uses companion matrix method to find roots. In case
2897  internal EVD solver fails do find eigenvalues, exception is
2898  generated.
2899 
2900  NOTE: roots are not "polished" and no matrix balancing is performed
2901  for them.
2902 
2903  -- ALGLIB --
2904  Copyright 24.02.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
2905  *************************************************************************/
2906  public static void polynomialsolve(double[] a, int n, out complex[] x, out polynomialsolverreport rep)
2907  {
2908  x = new complex[0];
2909  rep = new polynomialsolverreport();
2910  polynomialsolver.polynomialsolve(a, n, ref x, rep.innerobj, null);
2911  }
2912 
2913  public static void polynomialsolve(double[] a, int n, out complex[] x, out polynomialsolverreport rep, alglib.xparams _params)
2914  {
2915  x = new complex[0];
2916  rep = new polynomialsolverreport();
2917  polynomialsolver.polynomialsolve(a, n, ref x, rep.innerobj, _params);
2918  }
2919 
2920 }

2998 
2999  /*************************************************************************
3000  LEVENBERG-MARQUARDT-LIKE NONLINEAR SOLVER
3001 
3002  DESCRIPTION:
3003  This algorithm solves system of nonlinear equations
3004  F[0](x[0], ..., x[n-1]) = 0
3005  F[1](x[0], ..., x[n-1]) = 0
3006  ...
3007  F[M-1](x[0], ..., x[n-1]) = 0
3008  with M/N do not necessarily coincide. Algorithm converges quadratically
3009  under following conditions:
3010  * the solution set XS is nonempty
3011  * for some xs in XS there exist such neighbourhood N(xs) that:
3012  * vector function F(x) and its Jacobian J(x) are continuously
3013  differentiable on N
3014  * ||F(x)|| provides local error bound on N, i.e. there exists such
3015  c1, that ||F(x)||>c1*distance(x,XS)
3016  Note that these conditions are much more weaker than usual non-singularity
3017  conditions. For example, algorithm will converge for any affine function
3018  F (whether its Jacobian singular or not).
3019 
3020 
3021  REQUIREMENTS:
3022  Algorithm will request following information during its operation:
3023  * function vector F[] and Jacobian matrix at given point X
3024  * value of merit function f(x)=F[0]^2(x)+...+F[M-1]^2(x) at given point X
3025 
3026 
3027  USAGE:
3028  1. User initializes algorithm state with NLEQCreateLM() call
3029  2. User tunes solver parameters with NLEQSetCond(), NLEQSetStpMax() and
3030  other functions
3031  3. User calls NLEQSolve() function which takes algorithm state and
3032  pointers (delegates, etc.) to callback functions which calculate merit
3033  function value and Jacobian.
3034  4. User calls NLEQResults() to get solution
3035  5. Optionally, user may call NLEQRestartFrom() to solve another problem
3036  with same parameters (N/M) but another starting point and/or another
3037  function vector. NLEQRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized
3038  structure.
3039 
3040 
3041  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3042  N - space dimension, N>1:
3043  * if provided, only leading N elements of X are used
3044  * if not provided, determined automatically from size of X
3045  M - system size
3046  X - starting point
3047 
3048 
3049  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3050  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3051 
3052 
3053  NOTES:
3054  1. you may tune stopping conditions with NLEQSetCond() function
3055  2. if target function contains exp() or other fast growing functions, and
3056  optimization algorithm makes too large steps which leads to overflow,
3057  use NLEQSetStpMax() function to bound algorithm's steps.
3058  3. this algorithm is a slightly modified implementation of the method
3059  described in 'Levenberg-Marquardt method for constrained nonlinear
3060  equations with strong local convergence properties' by Christian Kanzow
3061  Nobuo Yamashita and Masao Fukushima and further developed in 'On the
3062  convergence of a New Levenberg-Marquardt Method' by Jin-yan Fan and
3063  Ya-Xiang Yuan.
3064 
3065 
3066  -- ALGLIB --
3067  Copyright 20.08.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
3068  *************************************************************************/
3069  public static void nleqcreatelm(int n, int m, double[] x, out nleqstate state)
3070  {
3071  state = new nleqstate();
3072  nleq.nleqcreatelm(n, m, x, state.innerobj, null);
3073  }

3103  /*************************************************************************
3104  This function sets stopping conditions for the nonlinear solver
3105 
3106  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3107  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3108  EpsF - >=0
3109  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
3110  the condition ||F||<=EpsF is satisfied

3112  iterations is unlimited.
3113

3204  /*************************************************************************
3205  This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear solver
3206 
3207  These functions accept following parameters:
3208  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
3209  value func at given point x
3210  jac - callback which calculates function vector fi[]
3211  and Jacobian jac at given point x

3213  can be null

3215  can be null

3225  }
3226 
3227  public static void nleqsolve(nleqstate state, ndimensional_func func, ndimensional_jac jac, ndimensional_rep rep, object obj, alglib.xparams _params)
3228  {
3229  if( func==null )
3230  throw new alglibexception("ALGLIB: error in 'nleqsolve()' (func is null)");
3231  if( jac==null )
3232  throw new alglibexception("ALGLIB: error in 'nleqsolve()' (jac is null)");
3233  while( alglib.nleqiteration(state, _params) )
3234  {
3235  if( state.needf )
3236  {
3237  func(state.x, ref state.innerobj.f, obj);
3238  continue;
3239  }
3240  if( state.needfij )
3241  {
3242  jac(state.x, state.innerobj.fi, state.innerobj.j, obj);
3243  continue;
3244  }
3245  if( state.innerobj.xupdated )
3246  {
3247  if( rep!=null )
3248  rep(state.innerobj.x, state.innerobj.f, obj);
3249  continue;
3250  }
3251  throw new alglibexception("ALGLIB: error in 'nleqsolve' (some derivatives were not provided?)");
3252  }
3253  }

3257  /*************************************************************************
3258  NLEQ solver results
3259 
3260  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3261  State - algorithm state.
3262 
3263  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3264  X - array[0..N-1], solution
3265  Rep - optimization report:
3266  * Rep.TerminationType completetion code:
3267  * -4 ERROR: algorithm has converged to the
3268  stationary point Xf which is local minimum of
3269  f=F[0]^2+...+F[m-1]^2, but is not solution of
3270  nonlinear system.
3271  * 1 sqrt(f)<=EpsF.
3272  * 5 MaxIts steps was taken
3273  * 7 stopping conditions are too stringent,
3274  further improvement is impossible
3275  * Rep.IterationsCount contains iterations count
3276  * NFEV countains number of function calculations
3277  * ActiveConstraints contains number of active constraints
3278 
3279  -- ALGLIB --
3280  Copyright 20.08.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey

3618  /*************************************************************************
3619  This function initializes linear CG Solver. This solver is used to solve
3620  symmetric positive definite problems. If you want to solve nonsymmetric
3621  (or non-positive definite) problem you may use LinLSQR solver provided by
3622  ALGLIB.
3623 
3624  USAGE:
3625  1. User initializes algorithm state with LinCGCreate() call
3626  2. User tunes solver parameters with LinCGSetCond() and other functions
3627  3. Optionally, user sets starting point with LinCGSetStartingPoint()
3628  4. User calls LinCGSolveSparse() function which takes algorithm state and
3629  SparseMatrix object.
3630  5. User calls LinCGResults() to get solution
3631  6. Optionally, user may call LinCGSolveSparse() again to solve another
3632  problem with different matrix and/or right part without reinitializing
3633  LinCGState structure.
3634 
3635  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3636  N - problem dimension, N>0
3637 
3638  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:

3759  /*************************************************************************
3760  Procedure for solution of A*x=b with sparse A.
3761 
3762  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3763  State - algorithm state
3764  A - sparse matrix in the CRS format (you MUST contvert it to
3765  CRS format by calling SparseConvertToCRS() function).
3766  IsUpper - whether upper or lower triangle of A is used:
3767  * IsUpper=True => only upper triangle is used and lower
3768  triangle is not referenced at all
3769  * IsUpper=False => only lower triangle is used and upper
3770  triangle is not referenced at all
3771  B - right part, array[N]
3772 
3773  RESULT:
3774  This function returns no result.
3775  You can get solution by calling LinCGResults()
3776 
3777  NOTE: this function uses lightweight preconditioning - multiplication by
3778  inverse of diag(A). If you want, you can turn preconditioning off by
3779  calling LinCGSetPrecUnit(). However, preconditioning cost is low and
3780  preconditioner is very important for solution of badly scaled
3781  problems.
3782 
3783  -- ALGLIB --
3784  Copyright 14.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3785  *************************************************************************/

3790  }

3810  * -5 input matrix is either not positive definite,
3811  too large or too small

3813  (ill conditioned problem)
3814  * 1 ||residual||<=EpsF*||b||
3815  * 5 MaxIts steps was taken

3817  best point found is returned

3819  * NMV countains number of matrix-vector calculations

3857  /*************************************************************************
3858  This function sets frequency of residual recalculations.
3859 
3860  Algorithm updates residual r_k using iterative formula, but recalculates
3861  it from scratch after each 10 iterations. It is done to avoid accumulation
3862  of numerical errors and to stop algorithm when r_k starts to grow.
3863 
3864  Such low update frequence (1/10) gives very little overhead, but makes
3865  algorithm a bit more robust against numerical errors. However, you may
3866  change it
3867 
3868  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3869  Freq - desired update frequency, Freq>=0.
3870  Zero value means that no updates will be done.
3871 
3872  -- ALGLIB --
3873  Copyright 14.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3874  *************************************************************************/
3875  public static void lincgsetrupdatefreq(lincgstate state, int freq)

3879  }

3966  /*************************************************************************
3967  Dense solver for A*x=b with N*N real matrix A and N*1 real vectorx x and
3968  b. This is "slow-but-feature rich" version of the linear solver. Faster
3969  version is RMatrixSolveFast() function.
3970 
3971  Algorithm features:
3972  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
3973  * condition number estimation
3974  * iterative refinement
3975  * O(N^3) complexity
3976 
3977  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
3978  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system
3979  ! and performs iterative refinement, which results in
3980  ! significant performance penalty when compared with "fast"
3981  ! version which just performs LU decomposition and calls
3982  ! triangular solver.
3983  !
3984  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
3985  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
3986  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
3987  ! calculations. It is also very significant on small matrices.
3988  !
3989  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
3990  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
3991  ! you to use faster solver, RMatrixSolveFast() function.
3992 
3993  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
3994  !
3995  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
3996  ! of this function:
3997  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
3998  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
3999  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4000  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4001  !
4002  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4003  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4004  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4005 
4006  INPUT PARAMETERS
4007  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
4008  N - size of A
4009  B - array[0..N-1], right part
4010 
4011  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
4012  Info - return code:
4013  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
4014  * -1 N<=0 was passed
4015  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
4016  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
4017  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
4018  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
4019  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
4020  X - array[N], it contains:
4021  * info>0 => solution
4022  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
4023 
4024  -- ALGLIB --
4025  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4026  *************************************************************************/
4027  public static void rmatrixsolve(double[,] a,
4028  int n,
4029  double[] b,
4030  ref int info,
4031  densesolverreport rep,
4032  ref double[] x,
4033  alglib.xparams _params)
4034  {
4035  double[,] bm = new double[0,0];
4036  double[,] xm = new double[0,0];
4037  int i_ = 0;
4038 
4039  info = 0;
4040  x = new double[0];
4041 
4042  if( n<=0 )
4043  {
4044  info = -1;
4045  return;
4046  }
4047  bm = new double[n, 1];
4048  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
4049  {
4050  bm[i_,0] = b[i_];
4051  }
4052  rmatrixsolvem(a, n, bm, 1, true, ref info, rep, ref xm, _params);
4053  x = new double[n];
4054  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
4055  {
4056  x[i_] = xm[i_,0];
4057  }
4058  }
4059 
4060 
4061  /*************************************************************************
4062  Dense solver.
4063 
4064  This subroutine solves a system A*x=b, where A is NxN non-denegerate
4065  real matrix, x and b are vectors. This is a "fast" version of linear
4066  solver which does NOT provide any additional functions like condition
4067  number estimation or iterative refinement.
4068 
4069  Algorithm features:
4070  * efficient algorithm O(N^3) complexity
4071  * no performance overhead from additional functionality
4072 
4073  If you need condition number estimation or iterative refinement, use more
4074  feature-rich version - RMatrixSolve().
4075 
4076  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4077  !
4078  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4079  ! of this function:
4080  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4081  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4082  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4083  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4084  !
4085  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4086  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4087  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4088 
4089  INPUT PARAMETERS
4090  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
4091  N - size of A
4092  B - array[0..N-1], right part
4093 
4094  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
4095  Info - return code:
4096  * -3 matrix is exactly singular (ill conditioned matrices
4097  are not recognized).
4098  * -1 N<=0 was passed
4099  * 1 task is solved
4100  B - array[N]:
4101  * info>0 => overwritten by solution
4102  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
4103 
4104  -- ALGLIB --
4105  Copyright 16.03.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
4106  *************************************************************************/
4107  public static void rmatrixsolvefast(double[,] a,
4108  int n,
4109  double[] b,
4110  ref int info,
4111  alglib.xparams _params)
4112  {
4113  int i = 0;
4114  int j = 0;
4115  int[] p = new int[0];
4116 
4117  a = (double[,])a.Clone();
4118  info = 0;
4119 
4120  if( n<=0 )
4121  {
4122  info = -1;
4123  return;
4124  }
4125  trfac.rmatrixlu(ref a, n, n, ref p, _params);
4126  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
4127  {
4128  if( (double)(a[i,i])==(double)(0) )
4129  {
4130  for(j=0; j<=n-1; j++)
4131  {
4132  b[j] = 0.0;
4133  }
4134  info = -3;
4135  return;
4136  }
4137  }
4138  rbasiclusolve(a, p, n, b, _params);
4139  info = 1;
4140  }
4141 
4142 
4143  /*************************************************************************
4144  Dense solver.
4145 
4146  Similar to RMatrixSolve() but solves task with multiple right parts (where
4147  b and x are NxM matrices). This is "slow-but-robust" version of linear
4148  solver with additional functionality like condition number estimation.
4149  There also exists faster version - RMatrixSolveMFast().
4150 
4151  Algorithm features:
4152  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
4153  * condition number estimation
4154  * optional iterative refinement
4155  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
4156 
4157  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
4158  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system
4159  ! and performs iterative refinement, which results in
4160  ! significant performance penalty when compared with "fast"
4161  ! version which just performs LU decomposition and calls
4162  ! triangular solver.
4163  !
4164  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
4165  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
4166  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
4167  ! calculations. It also very significant on small matrices.
4168  !
4169  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
4170  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
4171  ! you to use faster solver, RMatrixSolveMFast() function.
4172 
4173  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4174  !
4175  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4176  ! of this function:
4177  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4178  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4179  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4180  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4181  !
4182  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4183  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4184  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4185 
4186  INPUT PARAMETERS
4187  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
4188  N - size of A
4189  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
4190  M - right part size
4191  RFS - iterative refinement switch:
4192  * True - refinement is used.
4193  Less performance, more precision.
4194  * False - refinement is not used.
4195  More performance, less precision.
4196 
4197  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
4198  Info - return code:
4199  * -3 A is ill conditioned or singular.
4200  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
4201  * -1 N<=0 was passed
4202  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
4203  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
4204  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
4205  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
4206  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
4207  X - array[N], it contains:
4208  * info>0 => solution
4209  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
4210 
4211 
4212  -- ALGLIB --
4213  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4214  *************************************************************************/
4215  public static void rmatrixsolvem(double[,] a,
4216  int n,
4217  double[,] b,
4218  int m,
4219  bool rfs,
4220  ref int info,
4221  densesolverreport rep,
4222  ref double[,] x,
4223  alglib.xparams _params)
4224  {
4225  double[,] da = new double[0,0];
4226  double[,] emptya = new double[0,0];
4227  int[] p = new int[0];
4228  int i = 0;
4229  int i_ = 0;
4230 
4231  info = 0;
4232  x = new double[0,0];
4233 
4234 
4235  //
4236  // prepare: check inputs, allocate space...
4237  //
4238  if( n<=0 || m<=0 )
4239  {
4240  info = -1;
4241  return;
4242  }
4243  da = new double[n, n];
4244 
4245  //
4246  // 1. factorize matrix
4247  // 3. solve
4248  //
4249  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
4250  {
4251  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
4252  {
4253  da[i,i_] = a[i,i_];
4254  }
4255  }
4256  trfac.rmatrixlu(ref da, n, n, ref p, _params);
4257  if( rfs )
4258  {
4259  rmatrixlusolveinternal(da, p, n, a, true, b, m, ref info, rep, ref x, _params);
4260  }
4261  else
4262  {
4263  rmatrixlusolveinternal(da, p, n, emptya, false, b, m, ref info, rep, ref x, _params);
4264  }
4265  }

4268  /*************************************************************************
4269  Dense solver.
4270 
4271  Similar to RMatrixSolve() but solves task with multiple right parts (where
4272  b and x are NxM matrices). This is "fast" version of linear solver which
4273  does NOT offer additional functions like condition number estimation or
4274  iterative refinement.
4275 
4276  Algorithm features:
4277  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
4278  * no additional functionality, highest performance
4279 
4280  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4281  !
4282  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4283  ! of this function:
4284  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4285  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4286  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4287  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4288  !
4289  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4290  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4291  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4292 
4293  INPUT PARAMETERS
4294  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
4295  N - size of A
4296  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
4297  M - right part size
4298  RFS - iterative refinement switch:
4299  * True - refinement is used.
4300  Less performance, more precision.
4301  * False - refinement is not used.
4302  More performance, less precision.
4303 
4304  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
4305  Info - return code:
4306  * -3 matrix is exactly singular (ill conditioned matrices
4307  are not recognized).
4308  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
4309  * -1 N<=0 was passed
4310  * 1 task is solved
4311  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
4312  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
4313  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
4314  B - array[N]:
4315  * info>0 => overwritten by solution
4316  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
4317 
4318 
4319  -- ALGLIB --
4320  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4321  *************************************************************************/
4322  public static void rmatrixsolvemfast(double[,] a,
4323  int n,
4324  double[,] b,
4325  int m,
4326  ref int info,
4327  alglib.xparams _params)
4328  {
4329  double v = 0;
4330  int i = 0;
4331  int j = 0;
4332  int k = 0;
4333  int[] p = new int[0];
4334 
4335  a = (double[,])a.Clone();
4336  info = 0;
4337 
4338 
4339  //
4340  // Check for exact degeneracy
4341  //
4342  if( n<=0 || m<=0 )
4343  {
4344  info = -1;
4345  return;
4346  }
4347  trfac.rmatrixlu(ref a, n, n, ref p, _params);
4348  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
4349  {
4350  if( (double)(a[i,i])==(double)(0) )
4351  {
4352  for(j=0; j<=n-1; j++)
4353  {
4354  for(k=0; k<=m-1; k++)
4355  {
4356  b[j,k] = 0.0;
4357  }
4358  }
4359  info = -3;
4360  return;
4361  }
4362  }
4363 
4364  //
4365  // Solve with TRSM()
4366  //
4367  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
4368  {
4369  if( p[i]!=i )
4370  {
4371  for(j=0; j<=m-1; j++)
4372  {
4373  v = b[i,j];
4374  b[i,j] = b[p[i],j];
4375  b[p[i],j] = v;
4376  }
4377  }
4378  }
4379  ablas.rmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, false, true, 0, b, 0, 0, _params);
4380  ablas.rmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, true, false, 0, b, 0, 0, _params);
4381  info = 1;
4382  }

4384 
4385  /*************************************************************************
4386  Dense solver.
4387 
4388  This subroutine solves a system A*x=b, where A is NxN non-denegerate
4389  real matrix given by its LU decomposition, x and b are real vectors. This
4390  is "slow-but-robust" version of the linear LU-based solver. Faster version
4391  is RMatrixLUSolveFast() function.
4392 
4393  Algorithm features:
4394  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
4395  * O(N^2) complexity
4396  * condition number estimation
4397 
4398  No iterative refinement is provided because exact form of original matrix
4399  is not known to subroutine. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
4400  need iterative refinement.
4401 
4402  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
4403  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
4404  ! which results in 10-15x performance penalty when compared
4405  ! with "fast" version which just calls triangular solver.
4406  !
4407  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
4408  ! cost of large LU decomposition. However, if you call this
4409  ! function many times for the same left side, this overhead
4410  ! BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant for small-
4411  ! scale problems.
4412  !
4413  ! In such cases we strongly recommend you to use faster solver,
4414  ! RMatrixLUSolveFast() function.
4415 
4416  INPUT PARAMETERS
4417  LUA - array[N,N], LU decomposition, RMatrixLU result
4418  P - array[N], pivots array, RMatrixLU result
4419  N - size of A
4420  B - array[N], right part
4421 
4422  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
4423  Info - return code:
4424  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
4425  * -1 N<=0 was passed
4426  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
4427  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
4428  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
4429  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
4430  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
4431  X - array[N], it contains:
4432  * info>0 => solution
4433  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
4434 
4435 
4436  -- ALGLIB --
4437  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4438  *************************************************************************/

4888  /*************************************************************************
4889  Complex dense solver for A*X=B with N*N complex matrix A, N*M complex
4890  matrices X and B. "Slow-but-feature-rich" version which provides
4891  additional functions, at the cost of slower performance. Faster version
4892  may be invoked with CMatrixSolveMFast() function.
4893 
4894  Algorithm features:
4895  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
4896  * condition number estimation
4897  * iterative refinement
4898  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
4899 
4900  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
4901  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system
4902  ! and performs iterative refinement, which results in
4903  ! significant performance penalty when compared with "fast"
4904  ! version which just performs LU decomposition and calls
4905  ! triangular solver.
4906  !
4907  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
4908  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
4909  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
4910  ! calculations.
4911  !
4912  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
4913  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
4914  ! you to use faster solver, CMatrixSolveMFast() function.
4915 
4916  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4917  !
4918  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4919  ! of this function:
4920  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4921  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4922  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4923  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4924  !
4925  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4926  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4927  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4928 
4929  INPUT PARAMETERS
4930  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
4931  N - size of A
4932  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
4933  M - right part size
4934  RFS - iterative refinement switch:
4935  * True - refinement is used.
4936  Less performance, more precision.
4937  * False - refinement is not used.
4938  More performance, less precision.
4939 
4940  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
4941  Info - return code:
4942  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
4943  X is filled by zeros in such cases.
4944  * -1 N<=0 was passed
4945  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
4946  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
4947  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
4948  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
4949  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
4950  X - array[N,M], it contains:
4951  * info>0 => solution
4952  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
4953 
4954  -- ALGLIB --
4955  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4956  *************************************************************************/
4957  public static void cmatrixsolvem(complex[,] a,
4958  int n,
4959  complex[,] b,
4960  int m,
4961  bool rfs,
4962  ref int info,
4963  densesolverreport rep,
4964  ref complex[,] x,
4965  alglib.xparams _params)
4966  {
4967  complex[,] da = new complex[0,0];
4968  complex[,] emptya = new complex[0,0];
4969  int[] p = new int[0];
4970  int i = 0;
4971  int i_ = 0;
4972 
4973  info = 0;
4974  x = new complex[0,0];
4975 
4976 
4977  //
4978  // prepare: check inputs, allocate space...
4979  //
4980  if( n<=0 || m<=0 )
4981  {
4982  info = -1;
4983  return;
4984  }
4985  da = new complex[n, n];
4986 
4987  //
4988  // factorize, solve
4989  //
4990  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
4991  {
4992  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
4993  {
4994  da[i,i_] = a[i,i_];
4995  }
4996  }
4997  trfac.cmatrixlu(ref da, n, n, ref p, _params);
4998  if( rfs )
4999  {
5000  cmatrixlusolveinternal(da, p, n, a, true, b, m, ref info, rep, ref x, _params);
5001  }
5002  else
5003  {
5004  cmatrixlusolveinternal(da, p, n, emptya, false, b, m, ref info, rep, ref x, _params);
5005  }
5006  }

5009  /*************************************************************************
5010  Complex dense solver for A*X=B with N*N complex matrix A, N*M complex
5011  matrices X and B. "Fast-but-lightweight" version which provides just
5012  triangular solver - and no additional functions like iterative refinement
5013  or condition number estimation.
5014 
5015  Algorithm features:
5016  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
5017  * no additional time consuming functions
5018 
5019  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5020  !
5021  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5022  ! of this function:
5023  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5024  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
5025  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5026  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5027  !
5028  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5029  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5030  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5031 
5032  INPUT PARAMETERS
5033  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
5034  N - size of A
5035  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
5036  M - right part size
5037 
5038  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
5039  Info - return code:
5040  * -3 matrix is exactly singular (ill conditioned matrices
5041  are not recognized).
5042  * -1 N<=0 was passed
5043  * 1 task is solved
5044  B - array[N,M]:
5045  * info>0 => overwritten by solution
5046  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
5047 
5048  -- ALGLIB --
5049  Copyright 16.03.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
5050  *************************************************************************/
5051  public static void cmatrixsolvemfast(complex[,] a,
5052  int n,
5053  complex[,] b,
5054  int m,
5055  ref int info,
5056  alglib.xparams _params)
5057  {
5058  complex v = 0;
5059  int i = 0;
5060  int j = 0;
5061  int k = 0;
5062  int[] p = new int[0];
5063 
5064  a = (complex[,])a.Clone();
5065  info = 0;
5066 
5067 
5068  //
5069  // Check for exact degeneracy
5070  //
5071  if( n<=0 || m<=0 )
5072  {
5073  info = -1;
5074  return;
5075  }
5076  trfac.cmatrixlu(ref a, n, n, ref p, _params);
5077  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
5078  {
5079  if( a[i,i]==0 )
5080  {
5081  for(j=0; j<=n-1; j++)
5082  {
5083  for(k=0; k<=m-1; k++)
5084  {
5085  b[j,k] = 0.0;
5086  }
5087  }
5088  info = -3;
5089  return;
5090  }
5091  }
5092 
5093  //
5094  // Solve with TRSM()
5095  //
5096  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
5097  {
5098  if( p[i]!=i )
5099  {
5100  for(j=0; j<=m-1; j++)
5101  {
5102  v = b[i,j];
5103  b[i,j] = b[p[i],j];
5104  b[p[i],j] = v;
5105  }
5106  }
5107  }
5108  ablas.cmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, false, true, 0, b, 0, 0, _params);
5109  ablas.cmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, true, false, 0, b, 0, 0, _params);
5110  info = 1;
5111  }
5112 
5113 
5114  /*************************************************************************
5115  Complex dense solver for A*x=B with N*N complex matrix A and N*1 complex
5116  vectors x and b. "Slow-but-feature-rich" version of the solver.
5117 
5118  Algorithm features:
5119  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
5120  * condition number estimation
5121  * iterative refinement
5122  * O(N^3) complexity
5123 
5124  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
5125  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system
5126  ! and performs iterative refinement, which results in
5127  ! significant performance penalty when compared with "fast"
5128  ! version which just performs LU decomposition and calls
5129  ! triangular solver.
5130  !
5131  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
5132  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
5133  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
5134  ! calculations.
5135  !
5136  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
5137  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
5138  ! you to use faster solver, CMatrixSolveFast() function.
5139 
5140  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5141  !
5142  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5143  ! of this function:
5144  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5145  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
5146  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5147  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5148  !
5149  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5150  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5151  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5152 
5153  INPUT PARAMETERS
5154  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
5155  N - size of A
5156  B - array[0..N-1], right part
5157 
5158  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
5159  Info - return code:
5160  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
5161  * -1 N<=0 was passed
5162  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
5163  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
5164  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
5165  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
5166  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
5167  X - array[N], it contains:
5168  * info>0 => solution
5169  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
5170 
5171  -- ALGLIB --
5172  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5173  *************************************************************************/
5174  public static void cmatrixsolve(complex[,] a,
5175  int n,
5176  complex[] b,
5177  ref int info,
5178  densesolverreport rep,
5179  ref complex[] x,
5180  alglib.xparams _params)
5181  {
5182  complex[,] bm = new complex[0,0];
5183  complex[,] xm = new complex[0,0];
5184  int i_ = 0;
5185 
5186  info = 0;
5187  x = new complex[0];
5188 
5189  if( n<=0 )
5190  {
5191  info = -1;
5192  return;
5193  }
5194  bm = new complex[n, 1];
5195  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
5196  {
5197  bm[i_,0] = b[i_];
5198  }
5199  cmatrixsolvem(a, n, bm, 1, true, ref info, rep, ref xm, _params);
5200  x = new complex[n];
5201  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
5202  {
5203  x[i_] = xm[i_,0];
5204  }
5205  }

5502  ! with "fast" version which just calls triangular solver.
5503  !
5504  ! This performance penalty is insignificant when compared with
5505  ! cost of large LU decomposition. However, if you call this
5506  ! function many times for the same left side, this overhead
5507  ! BECOMES significant. It also becomes significant for small-
5508  ! scale problems.

5686 
5687  //
5688  // prepare: check inputs, allocate space...
5689  //

5691  {
5692  info = -1;
5693  return;

5703  /*************************************************************************
5704  Dense solver. Same as RMatrixMixedSolve(), but for complex matrices.
5705 
5706  Algorithm features:
5707  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
5708  * condition number estimation
5709  * iterative refinement
5710  * O(N^2) complexity
5711 
5712  INPUT PARAMETERS
5713  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
5714  LUA - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], LU decomposition, CMatrixLU result
5715  P - array[0..N-1], pivots array, CMatrixLU result
5716  N - size of A
5717  B - array[0..N-1], right part
5718 
5719  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
5720  Info - return code:
5721  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or exactly singular.
5722  * -1 N<=0 was passed
5723  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
5724  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
5725  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
5726  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
5727  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
5728  X - array[N], it contains:
5729  * info>0 => solution
5730  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
5731 
5732  -- ALGLIB --
5733  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5734  *************************************************************************/
5735  public static void cmatrixmixedsolve(complex[,] a,
5736  complex[,] lua,
5737  int[] p,
5738  int n,
5739  complex[] b,
5740  ref int info,
5741  densesolverreport rep,
5742  ref complex[] x,
5743  alglib.xparams _params)
5744  {
5745  complex[,] bm = new complex[0,0];
5746  complex[,] xm = new complex[0,0];
5747  int i_ = 0;
5748 
5749  info = 0;
5750  x = new complex[0];
5751 
5752  if( n<=0 )
5753  {
5754  info = -1;
5755  return;
5756  }
5757  bm = new complex[n, 1];
5758  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
5759  {
5760  bm[i_,0] = b[i_];
5761  }
5762  cmatrixmixedsolvem(a, lua, p, n, bm, 1, ref info, rep, ref xm, _params);
5763  x = new complex[n];
5764  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
5765  {
5766  x[i_] = xm[i_,0];
5767  }
5768  }

5771  /*************************************************************************
5772  Dense solver for A*X=B with N*N symmetric positive definite matrix A, and
5773  N*M vectors X and B. It is "slow-but-feature-rich" version of the solver.
5774 
5775  Algorithm features:
5776  * automatic detection of degenerate cases
5777  * condition number estimation
5778  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
5779  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
5780 
5781  No iterative refinement is provided because such partial representation of
5782  matrix does not allow efficient calculation of extra-precise matrix-vector
5783  products for large matrices. Use RMatrixSolve or RMatrixMixedSolve if you
5784  need iterative refinement.
5785 
5786  IMPORTANT: ! this function is NOT the most efficient linear solver provided
5787  ! by ALGLIB. It estimates condition number of linear system,
5788  ! which results in significant performance penalty when
5789  ! compared with "fast" version which just performs Cholesky
5790  ! decomposition and calls triangular solver.
5791  !
5792  ! This performance penalty is especially visible in the
5793  ! multithreaded mode, because both condition number estimation
5794  ! and iterative refinement are inherently sequential
5795  ! calculations.
5796  !
5797  ! Thus, if you need high performance and if you are pretty sure
5798  ! that your system is well conditioned, we strongly recommend
5799  ! you to use faster solver, SPDMatrixSolveMFast() function.
5800 
5801  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5802  !
5803  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5804  ! of this function:
5805  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5806  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
5807  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5808  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5809  !
5810  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5811  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5812  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5813 
5814  INPUT PARAMETERS
5815  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
5816  N - size of A
5817  IsUpper - what half of A is provided
5818  B - array[0..N-1,0..M-1], right part
5819  M - right part size
5820 
5821  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
5822  Info - return code:
5823  * -3 matrix is very badly conditioned or non-SPD.
5824  * -1 N<=0 was passed
5825  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
5826  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
5827  Rep - additional report, following fields are set:
5828  * rep.r1 condition number in 1-norm
5829  * rep.rinf condition number in inf-norm
5830  X - array[N,M], it contains:
5831  * info>0 => solution
5832  * info=-3 => filled by zeros
5833 
5834  -- ALGLIB --
5835  Copyright 27.01.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5836  *************************************************************************/
5837  public static void spdmatrixsolvem(double[,] a,
5838  int n,
5839  bool isupper,
5840  double[,] b,
5841  int m,
5842  ref int info,
5843  densesolverreport rep,
5844  ref double[,] x,
5845  alglib.xparams _params)
5846  {
5847  double[,] da = new double[0,0];
5848  int i = 0;
5849  int j = 0;
5850  int j1 = 0;
5851  int j2 = 0;
5852  int i_ = 0;
5853 
5854  info = 0;
5855  x = new double[0,0];
5856 
5857 
5858  //
5859  // prepare: check inputs, allocate space...
5860  //
5861  if( n<=0 || m<=0 )
5862  {
5863  info = -1;
5864  return;
5865  }
5866  da = new double[n, n];
5867 
5868  //
5869  // factorize
5870  // solve
5871  //
5872  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
5873  {
5874  if( isupper )
5875  {
5876  j1 = i;
5877  j2 = n-1;
5878  }
5879  else
5880  {
5881  j1 = 0;
5882  j2 = i;
5883  }
5884  for(i_=j1; i_<=j2;i_++)
5885  {
5886  da[i,i_] = a[i,i_];
5887  }
5888  }
5889  if( !trfac.spdmatrixcholesky(ref da, n, isupper, _params) )
5890  {
5891  x = new double[n, m];
5892  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
5893  {
5894  for(j=0; j<=m-1; j++)
5895  {
5896  x[i,j] = 0;
5897  }
5898  }
5899  rep.r1 = 0;
5900  rep.rinf = 0;
5901  info = -3;
5902  return;
5903  }
5904  info = 1;
5905  spdmatrixcholeskysolveinternal(da, n, isupper, a, true, b, m, ref info, rep, ref x, _params);
5906  }
5907

5909  /*************************************************************************
5910  Dense solver for A*X=B with N*N symmetric positive definite matrix A, and
5911  N*M vectors X and B. It is "fast-but-lightweight" version of the solver.
5912 
5913  Algorithm features:
5914  * O(N^3+M*N^2) complexity
5915  * matrix is represented by its upper or lower triangle
5916  * no additional time consuming features
5917 
5918  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5919  !
5920  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5921  ! of this function:
5922  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5923  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
5924  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5925  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)

5927  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5928  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5929  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.

5932  A - array[0..N-1,0..N-1], system matrix
5933  N - size of A

5950  public static void spdmatrixsolvemfast(double[,] a,
5951  int n,
5952  bool isupper,
5953  double[,] b,
5954  int m,
5955  ref int info,
5956  alglib.xparams _params)
5957  {
5958  int i = 0;
5959  int j = 0;
5960 
5961  a = (double[,])a.Clone();
5962  info = 0;
5963 
5964  info = 1;
5965  if( n<=0 )
5966  {
5967  info = -1;
5968  return;
5969  }
5970  if( !trfac.spdmatrixcholesky(ref a, n, isupper, _params) )
5971  {
5972  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
5973  {
5974  for(j=0; j<=m-1; j++)
5975  {
5976  b[i,j] = 0.0;
5977  }
5978  }
5979  info = -3;
5980  return;
5981  }
5982  if( isupper )
5983  {
5984  ablas.rmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, true, false, 1, b, 0, 0, _params);
5985  ablas.rmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, true, false, 0, b, 0, 0, _params);
5986  }
5987  else
5988  {
5989  ablas.rmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, false, false, 0, b, 0, 0, _params);
5990  ablas.rmatrixlefttrsm(n, m, a, 0, 0, false, false, 1, b, 0, 0, _params);
5991  }
5992  }
