8544 
8545 
8546  public const double atol = 1.0E-6;
8547  public const double btol = 1.0E-6;
8548 
8549 
8550  /*************************************************************************
8551  This function initializes linear LSQR Solver. This solver is used to solve
8552  non-symmetric (and, possibly, non-square) problems. Least squares solution
8553  is returned for non-compatible systems.
8554 
8555  USAGE:
8556  1. User initializes algorithm state with LinLSQRCreate() call
8557  2. User tunes solver parameters with LinLSQRSetCond() and other functions
8558  3. User calls LinLSQRSolveSparse() function which takes algorithm state
8559  and SparseMatrix object.
8560  4. User calls LinLSQRResults() to get solution
8561  5. Optionally, user may call LinLSQRSolveSparse() again to solve another
8562  problem with different matrix and/or right part without reinitializing
8563  LinLSQRState structure.
8564 
8565  INPUT PARAMETERS:
8566  M - number of rows in A
8567  N - number of variables, N>0
8568 
8569  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8570  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8571 
8572  NOTE: see also linlsqrcreatebuf() for version which reuses previously
8573  allocated place as much as possible.
8574 
8575  -- ALGLIB --
8576  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8577  *************************************************************************/
8578  public static void linlsqrcreate(int m,
8579  int n,
8580  linlsqrstate state,
8581  alglib.xparams _params)
8582  {
8583  alglib.ap.assert(m>0, "LinLSQRCreate: M<=0");
8584  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "LinLSQRCreate: N<=0");
8585  linlsqrcreatebuf(m, n, state, _params);
8586  }
8587 
8588 
8589  /*************************************************************************
8590  This function initializes linear LSQR Solver. It provides exactly same
8591  functionality as linlsqrcreate(), but reuses previously allocated space
8592  as much as possible.
8593 
8594  INPUT PARAMETERS:
8595  M - number of rows in A
8596  N - number of variables, N>0
8597 
8598  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8599  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8600 
8601  -- ALGLIB --
8602  Copyright 14.11.2018 by Bochkanov Sergey
8603  *************************************************************************/
8604  public static void linlsqrcreatebuf(int m,
8605  int n,
8606  linlsqrstate state,
8607  alglib.xparams _params)
8608  {
8609  int i = 0;
8610 
8611  alglib.ap.assert(m>0, "LinLSQRCreateBuf: M<=0");
8612  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "LinLSQRCreateBuf: N<=0");
8613  state.m = m;
8614  state.n = n;
8615  state.prectype = 0;
8616  state.epsa = atol;
8617  state.epsb = btol;
8618  state.epsc = 1/Math.Sqrt(math.machineepsilon);
8619  state.maxits = 0;
8620  state.lambdai = 0;
8621  state.xrep = false;
8622  state.running = false;
8623  state.repiterationscount = 0;
8624 
8625  //
8626  // * allocate arrays
8627  // * set RX to NAN (just for the case user calls Results() without
8628  // calling SolveSparse()
8629  // * set B to zero
8630  //
8631  normestimator.normestimatorcreate(m, n, 2, 2, state.nes, _params);
8632  state.rx = new double[state.n];
8633  state.ui = new double[state.m+state.n];
8634  state.uip1 = new double[state.m+state.n];
8635  state.vip1 = new double[state.n];
8636  state.vi = new double[state.n];
8637  state.omegai = new double[state.n];
8638  state.omegaip1 = new double[state.n];
8639  state.d = new double[state.n];
8640  state.x = new double[state.m+state.n];
8641  state.mv = new double[state.m+state.n];
8642  state.mtv = new double[state.n];
8643  state.b = new double[state.m];
8644  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
8645  {
8646  state.rx[i] = Double.NaN;
8647  }
8648  for(i=0; i<=m-1; i++)
8649  {
8650  state.b[i] = 0;
8651  }
8652  state.rstate.ia = new int[1+1];
8653  state.rstate.ra = new double[0+1];
8654  state.rstate.stage = -1;
8655  }
8656 
8657 
8658  /*************************************************************************
8659  This function sets right part. By default, right part is zero.
8660 
8661  INPUT PARAMETERS:
8662  B - right part, array[N].
8663 
8664  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8665  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8666 
8667  -- ALGLIB --
8668  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8669  *************************************************************************/
8670  public static void linlsqrsetb(linlsqrstate state,
8671  double[] b,
8672  alglib.xparams _params)
8673  {
8674  int i = 0;
8675 
8676  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRSetB: you can not change B when LinLSQRIteration is running");
8677  alglib.ap.assert(state.m<=alglib.ap.len(b), "LinLSQRSetB: Length(B)<M");
8678  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(b, state.m, _params), "LinLSQRSetB: B contains infinite or NaN values");
8679  state.bnorm2 = 0;
8680  for(i=0; i<=state.m-1; i++)
8681  {
8682  state.b[i] = b[i];
8683  state.bnorm2 = state.bnorm2+b[i]*b[i];
8684  }
8685  }
8686 
8687 
8688  /*************************************************************************
8689  This function changes preconditioning settings of LinLSQQSolveSparse()
8690  function. By default, SolveSparse() uses diagonal preconditioner, but if
8691  you want to use solver without preconditioning, you can call this function
8692  which forces solver to use unit matrix for preconditioning.
8693 
8694  INPUT PARAMETERS:
8695  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8696 
8697  -- ALGLIB --
8698  Copyright 19.11.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
8699  *************************************************************************/
8700  public static void linlsqrsetprecunit(linlsqrstate state,
8701  alglib.xparams _params)
8702  {
8703  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRSetPrecUnit: you can not change preconditioner, because function LinLSQRIteration is running!");
8704  state.prectype = -1;
8705  }
8706 
8707 
8708  /*************************************************************************
8709  This function changes preconditioning settings of LinCGSolveSparse()
8710  function. LinCGSolveSparse() will use diagonal of the system matrix as
8711  preconditioner. This preconditioning mode is active by default.
8712 
8713  INPUT PARAMETERS:
8714  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8715 
8716  -- ALGLIB --
8717  Copyright 19.11.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
8718  *************************************************************************/
8719  public static void linlsqrsetprecdiag(linlsqrstate state,
8720  alglib.xparams _params)
8721  {
8722  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRSetPrecDiag: you can not change preconditioner, because function LinCGIteration is running!");
8723  state.prectype = 0;
8724  }
8725 
8726 
8727  /*************************************************************************
8728  This function sets optional Tikhonov regularization coefficient.
8729  It is zero by default.
8730 
8731  INPUT PARAMETERS:
8732  LambdaI - regularization factor, LambdaI>=0
8733 
8734  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8735  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8736 
8737  -- ALGLIB --
8738  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8739  *************************************************************************/
8740  public static void linlsqrsetlambdai(linlsqrstate state,
8741  double lambdai,
8742  alglib.xparams _params)
8743  {
8744  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRSetLambdaI: you can not set LambdaI, because function LinLSQRIteration is running");
8745  alglib.ap.assert(math.isfinite(lambdai) && (double)(lambdai)>=(double)(0), "LinLSQRSetLambdaI: LambdaI is infinite or NaN");
8746  state.lambdai = lambdai;
8747  }
8748 
8749 
8750  /*************************************************************************
8751 
8752  -- ALGLIB --
8753  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8754  *************************************************************************/
8755  public static bool linlsqriteration(linlsqrstate state,
8756  alglib.xparams _params)
8757  {
8758  bool result = new bool();
8759  int summn = 0;
8760  double bnorm = 0;
8761  int i = 0;
8762  int i_ = 0;
8763 
8764 
8765  //
8766  // Reverse communication preparations
8767  // I know it looks ugly, but it works the same way
8768  // anywhere from C++ to Python.
8769  //
8770  // This code initializes locals by:
8771  // * random values determined during code
8772  // generation - on first subroutine call
8773  // * values from previous call - on subsequent calls
8774  //
8775  if( state.rstate.stage>=0 )
8776  {
8777  summn = state.rstate.ia[0];
8778  i = state.rstate.ia[1];
8779  bnorm = state.rstate.ra[0];
8780  }
8781  else
8782  {
8783  summn = 359;
8784  i = -58;
8785  bnorm = -919;
8786  }
8787  if( state.rstate.stage==0 )
8788  {
8789  goto lbl_0;
8790  }
8791  if( state.rstate.stage==1 )
8792  {
8793  goto lbl_1;
8794  }
8795  if( state.rstate.stage==2 )
8796  {
8797  goto lbl_2;
8798  }
8799  if( state.rstate.stage==3 )
8800  {
8801  goto lbl_3;
8802  }
8803  if( state.rstate.stage==4 )
8804  {
8805  goto lbl_4;
8806  }
8807  if( state.rstate.stage==5 )
8808  {
8809  goto lbl_5;
8810  }
8811  if( state.rstate.stage==6 )
8812  {
8813  goto lbl_6;
8814  }
8815 
8816  //
8817  // Routine body
8818  //
8819  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(state.b)>0, "LinLSQRIteration: using non-allocated array B");
8820  summn = state.m+state.n;
8821  bnorm = Math.Sqrt(state.bnorm2);
8822  state.userterminationneeded = false;
8823  state.running = true;
8824  state.repnmv = 0;
8825  state.repiterationscount = 0;
8826  state.r2 = state.bnorm2;
8827  clearrfields(state, _params);
8828 
8829  //
8830  //estimate for ANorm
8831  //
8832  normestimator.normestimatorrestart(state.nes, _params);
8833  lbl_7:
8834  if( !normestimator.normestimatoriteration(state.nes, _params) )
8835  {
8836  goto lbl_8;
8837  }
8838  if( !state.nes.needmv )
8839  {
8840  goto lbl_9;
8841  }
8842  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
8843  {
8844  state.x[i_] = state.nes.x[i_];
8845  }
8846  state.repnmv = state.repnmv+1;
8847  clearrfields(state, _params);
8848  state.needmv = true;
8849  state.rstate.stage = 0;
8850  goto lbl_rcomm;
8851  lbl_0:
8852  state.needmv = false;
8853  for(i_=0; i_<=state.m-1;i_++)
8854  {
8855  state.nes.mv[i_] = state.mv[i_];
8856  }
8857  goto lbl_7;
8858  lbl_9:
8859  if( !state.nes.needmtv )
8860  {
8861  goto lbl_11;
8862  }
8863  for(i_=0; i_<=state.m-1;i_++)
8864  {
8865  state.x[i_] = state.nes.x[i_];
8866  }
8867 
8868  //
8869  //matrix-vector multiplication
8870  //
8871  state.repnmv = state.repnmv+1;
8872  clearrfields(state, _params);
8873  state.needmtv = true;
8874  state.rstate.stage = 1;
8875  goto lbl_rcomm;
8876  lbl_1:
8877  state.needmtv = false;
8878  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
8879  {
8880  state.nes.mtv[i_] = state.mtv[i_];
8881  }
8882  goto lbl_7;
8883  lbl_11:
8884  goto lbl_7;
8885  lbl_8:
8886  normestimator.normestimatorresults(state.nes, ref state.anorm, _params);
8887 
8888  //
8889  //initialize .RX by zeros
8890  //
8891  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
8892  {
8893  state.rx[i] = 0;
8894  }
8895 
8896  //
8897  //output first report
8898  //
8899  if( !state.xrep )
8900  {
8901  goto lbl_13;
8902  }
8903  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
8904  {
8905  state.x[i_] = state.rx[i_];
8906  }
8907  clearrfields(state, _params);
8908  state.xupdated = true;
8909  state.rstate.stage = 2;
8910  goto lbl_rcomm;
8911  lbl_2:
8912  state.xupdated = false;
8913  lbl_13:
8914 
8915  //
8916  // LSQR, Step 0.
8917  //
8918  // Algorithm outline corresponds to one which was described at p.50 of
8919  // "LSQR - an algorithm for sparse linear equations and sparse least
8920  // squares" by C.Paige and M.Saunders with one small addition - we
8921  // explicitly extend system matrix by additional N lines in order
8922  // to handle non-zero lambda, i.e. original A is replaced by
8923  // [ A ]
8924  // A_mod = [ ]
8925  // [ lambda*I ].
8926  //
8927  // Step 0:
8928  // x[0] = 0
8929  // beta[1]*u[1] = b
8930  // alpha[1]*v[1] = A_mod'*u[1]
8931  // w[1] = v[1]
8932  // phiBar[1] = beta[1]
8933  // rhoBar[1] = alpha[1]
8934  // d[0] = 0
8935  //
8936  // NOTE:
8937  // There are three criteria for stopping:
8938  // (S0) maximum number of iterations
8939  // (S1) ||Rk||<=EpsB*||B||;
8940  // (S2) ||A^T*Rk||/(||A||*||Rk||)<=EpsA.
8941  // It is very important that S2 always checked AFTER S1. It is necessary
8942  // to avoid division by zero when Rk=0.
8943  //
8944  state.betai = bnorm;
8945  if( (double)(state.betai)==(double)(0) )
8946  {
8947 
8948  //
8949  // Zero right part
8950  //
8951  state.running = false;
8952  state.repterminationtype = 1;
8953  result = false;
8954  return result;
8955  }
8956  for(i=0; i<=summn-1; i++)
8957  {
8958  if( i<state.m )
8959  {
8960  state.ui[i] = state.b[i]/state.betai;
8961  }
8962  else
8963  {
8964  state.ui[i] = 0;
8965  }
8966  state.x[i] = state.ui[i];
8967  }
8968  state.repnmv = state.repnmv+1;
8969  clearrfields(state, _params);
8970  state.needmtv = true;
8971  state.rstate.stage = 3;
8972  goto lbl_rcomm;
8973  lbl_3:
8974  state.needmtv = false;
8975  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
8976  {
8977  state.mtv[i] = state.mtv[i]+state.lambdai*state.ui[state.m+i];
8978  }
8979  state.alphai = 0;
8980  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
8981  {
8982  state.alphai = state.alphai+state.mtv[i]*state.mtv[i];
8983  }
8984  state.alphai = Math.Sqrt(state.alphai);
8985  if( (double)(state.alphai)==(double)(0) )
8986  {
8987 
8988  //
8989  // Orthogonality stopping criterion is met
8990  //
8991  state.running = false;
8992  state.repterminationtype = 4;
8993  result = false;
8994  return result;
8995  }
8996  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
8997  {
8998  state.vi[i] = state.mtv[i]/state.alphai;
8999  state.omegai[i] = state.vi[i];
9000  }
9001  state.phibari = state.betai;
9002  state.rhobari = state.alphai;
9003  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9004  {
9005  state.d[i] = 0;
9006  }
9007  state.dnorm = 0;
9008 
9009  //
9010  // Steps I=1, 2, ...
9011  //
9012  lbl_15:
9013  if( false )
9014  {
9015  goto lbl_16;
9016  }
9017 
9018  //
9019  // At I-th step State.RepIterationsCount=I.
9020  //
9021  state.repiterationscount = state.repiterationscount+1;
9022 
9023  //
9024  // Bidiagonalization part:
9025  // beta[i+1]*u[i+1] = A_mod*v[i]-alpha[i]*u[i]
9026  // alpha[i+1]*v[i+1] = A_mod'*u[i+1] - beta[i+1]*v[i]
9027  //
9028  // NOTE: beta[i+1]=0 or alpha[i+1]=0 will lead to successful termination
9029  // in the end of the current iteration. In this case u/v are zero.
9030  // NOTE2: algorithm won't fail on zero alpha or beta (there will be no
9031  // division by zero because it will be stopped BEFORE division
9032  // occurs). However, near-zero alpha and beta won't stop algorithm
9033  // and, although no division by zero will happen, orthogonality
9034  // in U and V will be lost.
9035  //
9036  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
9037  {
9038  state.x[i_] = state.vi[i_];
9039  }
9040  state.repnmv = state.repnmv+1;
9041  clearrfields(state, _params);
9042  state.needmv = true;
9043  state.rstate.stage = 4;
9044  goto lbl_rcomm;
9045  lbl_4:
9046  state.needmv = false;
9047  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9048  {
9049  state.mv[state.m+i] = state.lambdai*state.vi[i];
9050  }
9051  state.betaip1 = 0;
9052  for(i=0; i<=summn-1; i++)
9053  {
9054  state.uip1[i] = state.mv[i]-state.alphai*state.ui[i];
9055  state.betaip1 = state.betaip1+state.uip1[i]*state.uip1[i];
9056  }
9057  if( (double)(state.betaip1)!=(double)(0) )
9058  {
9059  state.betaip1 = Math.Sqrt(state.betaip1);
9060  for(i=0; i<=summn-1; i++)
9061  {
9062  state.uip1[i] = state.uip1[i]/state.betaip1;
9063  }
9064  }
9065  for(i_=0; i_<=state.m-1;i_++)
9066  {
9067  state.x[i_] = state.uip1[i_];
9068  }
9069  state.repnmv = state.repnmv+1;
9070  clearrfields(state, _params);
9071  state.needmtv = true;
9072  state.rstate.stage = 5;
9073  goto lbl_rcomm;
9074  lbl_5:
9075  state.needmtv = false;
9076  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9077  {
9078  state.mtv[i] = state.mtv[i]+state.lambdai*state.uip1[state.m+i];
9079  }
9080  state.alphaip1 = 0;
9081  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9082  {
9083  state.vip1[i] = state.mtv[i]-state.betaip1*state.vi[i];
9084  state.alphaip1 = state.alphaip1+state.vip1[i]*state.vip1[i];
9085  }
9086  if( (double)(state.alphaip1)!=(double)(0) )
9087  {
9088  state.alphaip1 = Math.Sqrt(state.alphaip1);
9089  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9090  {
9091  state.vip1[i] = state.vip1[i]/state.alphaip1;
9092  }
9093  }
9094 
9095  //
9096  // Build next orthogonal transformation
9097  //
9098  state.rhoi = apserv.safepythag2(state.rhobari, state.betaip1, _params);
9099  state.ci = state.rhobari/state.rhoi;
9100  state.si = state.betaip1/state.rhoi;
9101  state.theta = state.si*state.alphaip1;
9102  state.rhobarip1 = -(state.ci*state.alphaip1);
9103  state.phii = state.ci*state.phibari;
9104  state.phibarip1 = state.si*state.phibari;
9105 
9106  //
9107  // Update .RNorm
9108  //
9109  // This tricky formula is necessary because simply writing
9110  // State.R2:=State.PhiBarIP1*State.PhiBarIP1 does NOT guarantees
9111  // monotonic decrease of R2. Roundoff error combined with 80-bit
9112  // precision used internally by Intel chips allows R2 to increase
9113  // slightly in some rare, but possible cases. This property is
9114  // undesirable, so we prefer to guard against R increase.
9115  //
9116  state.r2 = Math.Min(state.r2, state.phibarip1*state.phibarip1);
9117 
9118  //
9119  // Update d and DNorm, check condition-related stopping criteria
9120  //
9121  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9122  {
9123  state.d[i] = 1/state.rhoi*(state.vi[i]-state.theta*state.d[i]);
9124  state.dnorm = state.dnorm+state.d[i]*state.d[i];
9125  }
9126  if( (double)(Math.Sqrt(state.dnorm)*state.anorm)>=(double)(state.epsc) )
9127  {
9128  state.running = false;
9129  state.repterminationtype = 7;
9130  result = false;
9131  return result;
9132  }
9133 
9134  //
9135  // Update x, output report
9136  //
9137  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9138  {
9139  state.rx[i] = state.rx[i]+state.phii/state.rhoi*state.omegai[i];
9140  }
9141  if( !state.xrep )
9142  {
9143  goto lbl_17;
9144  }
9145  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
9146  {
9147  state.x[i_] = state.rx[i_];
9148  }
9149  clearrfields(state, _params);
9150  state.xupdated = true;
9151  state.rstate.stage = 6;
9152  goto lbl_rcomm;
9153  lbl_6:
9154  state.xupdated = false;
9155  lbl_17:
9156 
9157  //
9158  // Check stopping criteria
9159  // 1. achieved required number of iterations;
9160  // 2. ||Rk||<=EpsB*||B||;
9161  // 3. ||A^T*Rk||/(||A||*||Rk||)<=EpsA;
9162  //
9163  if( state.maxits>0 && state.repiterationscount>=state.maxits )
9164  {
9165 
9166  //
9167  // Achieved required number of iterations
9168  //
9169  state.running = false;
9170  state.repterminationtype = 5;
9171  result = false;
9172  return result;
9173  }
9174  if( (double)(state.phibarip1)<=(double)(state.epsb*bnorm) )
9175  {
9176 
9177  //
9178  // ||Rk||<=EpsB*||B||, here ||Rk||=PhiBar
9179  //
9180  state.running = false;
9181  state.repterminationtype = 1;
9182  result = false;
9183  return result;
9184  }
9185  if( (double)(state.alphaip1*Math.Abs(state.ci)/state.anorm)<=(double)(state.epsa) )
9186  {
9187 
9188  //
9189  // ||A^T*Rk||/(||A||*||Rk||)<=EpsA, here ||A^T*Rk||=PhiBar*Alpha[i+1]*|.C|
9190  //
9191  state.running = false;
9192  state.repterminationtype = 4;
9193  result = false;
9194  return result;
9195  }
9196  if( state.userterminationneeded )
9197  {
9198 
9199  //
9200  // User requested termination
9201  //
9202  state.running = false;
9203  state.repterminationtype = 8;
9204  result = false;
9205  return result;
9206  }
9207 
9208  //
9209  // Update omega
9210  //
9211  for(i=0; i<=state.n-1; i++)
9212  {
9213  state.omegaip1[i] = state.vip1[i]-state.theta/state.rhoi*state.omegai[i];
9214  }
9215 
9216  //
9217  // Prepare for the next iteration - rename variables:
9218  // u[i] := u[i+1]
9219  // v[i] := v[i+1]
9220  // rho[i] := rho[i+1]
9221  // ...
9222  //
9223  for(i_=0; i_<=summn-1;i_++)
9224  {
9225  state.ui[i_] = state.uip1[i_];
9226  }
9227  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
9228  {
9229  state.vi[i_] = state.vip1[i_];
9230  }
9231  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
9232  {
9233  state.omegai[i_] = state.omegaip1[i_];
9234  }
9235  state.alphai = state.alphaip1;
9236  state.betai = state.betaip1;
9237  state.phibari = state.phibarip1;
9238  state.rhobari = state.rhobarip1;
9239  goto lbl_15;
9240  lbl_16:
9241  result = false;
9242  return result;
9243 
9244  //
9245  // Saving state
9246  //
9247  lbl_rcomm:
9248  result = true;
9249  state.rstate.ia[0] = summn;
9250  state.rstate.ia[1] = i;
9251  state.rstate.ra[0] = bnorm;
9252  return result;
9253  }
9254 
9255 
9256  /*************************************************************************
9257  Procedure for solution of A*x=b with sparse A.
9258 
9259  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9260  State - algorithm state
9261  A - sparse M*N matrix in the CRS format (you MUST contvert it
9262  to CRS format by calling SparseConvertToCRS() function
9263  BEFORE you pass it to this function).
9264  B - right part, array[M]
9265 
9266  RESULT:
9267  This function returns no result.
9268  You can get solution by calling LinCGResults()
9269 
9270  NOTE: this function uses lightweight preconditioning - multiplication by
9271  inverse of diag(A). If you want, you can turn preconditioning off by
9272  calling LinLSQRSetPrecUnit(). However, preconditioning cost is low
9273  and preconditioner is very important for solution of badly scaled
9274  problems.
9275 
9276  -- ALGLIB --
9277  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
9278  *************************************************************************/
9279  public static void linlsqrsolvesparse(linlsqrstate state,
9280  sparse.sparsematrix a,
9281  double[] b,
9282  alglib.xparams _params)
9283  {
9284  int n = 0;
9285  int i = 0;
9286  int j = 0;
9287  int t0 = 0;
9288  int t1 = 0;
9289  double v = 0;
9290 
9291  n = state.n;
9292  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRSolveSparse: you can not call this function when LinLSQRIteration is running");
9293  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(b)>=state.m, "LinLSQRSolveSparse: Length(B)<M");
9294  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(b, state.m, _params), "LinLSQRSolveSparse: B contains infinite or NaN values");
9295 
9296  //
9297  // Allocate temporaries
9298  //
9299  apserv.rvectorsetlengthatleast(ref state.tmpd, n, _params);
9300  apserv.rvectorsetlengthatleast(ref state.tmpx, n, _params);
9301 
9302  //
9303  // Compute diagonal scaling matrix D
9304  //
9305  if( state.prectype==0 )
9306  {
9307 
9308  //
9309  // Default preconditioner - inverse of column norms
9310  //
9311  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
9312  {
9313  state.tmpd[i] = 0;
9314  }
9315  t0 = 0;
9316  t1 = 0;
9317  while( sparse.sparseenumerate(a, ref t0, ref t1, ref i, ref j, ref v, _params) )
9318  {
9319  state.tmpd[j] = state.tmpd[j]+math.sqr(v);
9320  }
9321  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
9322  {
9323  if( (double)(state.tmpd[i])>(double)(0) )
9324  {
9325  state.tmpd[i] = 1/Math.Sqrt(state.tmpd[i]);
9326  }
9327  else
9328  {
9329  state.tmpd[i] = 1;
9330  }
9331  }
9332  }
9333  else
9334  {
9335 
9336  //
9337  // No diagonal scaling
9338  //
9339  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
9340  {
9341  state.tmpd[i] = 1;
9342  }
9343  }
9344 
9345  //
9346  // Solve.
9347  //
9348  // Instead of solving A*x=b we solve preconditioned system (A*D)*(inv(D)*x)=b.
9349  // Transformed A is not calculated explicitly, we just modify multiplication
9350  // by A or A'. After solution we modify State.RX so it will store untransformed
9351  // variables
9352  //
9353  linlsqrsetb(state, b, _params);
9354  linlsqrrestart(state, _params);
9355  while( linlsqriteration(state, _params) )
9356  {
9357  if( state.needmv )
9358  {
9359  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
9360  {
9361  state.tmpx[i] = state.tmpd[i]*state.x[i];
9362  }
9363  sparse.sparsemv(a, state.tmpx, ref state.mv, _params);
9364  }
9365  if( state.needmtv )
9366  {
9367  sparse.sparsemtv(a, state.x, ref state.mtv, _params);
9368  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
9369  {
9370  state.mtv[i] = state.tmpd[i]*state.mtv[i];
9371  }
9372  }
9373  }
9374  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
9375  {
9376  state.rx[i] = state.tmpd[i]*state.rx[i];
9377  }
9378  }
9379 
9380 
9381  /*************************************************************************
9382  This function sets stopping criteria.
9383 
9384  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9385  EpsA - algorithm will be stopped if ||A^T*Rk||/(||A||*||Rk||)<=EpsA.
9386  EpsB - algorithm will be stopped if ||Rk||<=EpsB*||B||
9387  MaxIts - algorithm will be stopped if number of iterations
9388  more than MaxIts.
9389 
9390  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
9391  State - structure which stores algorithm state
9392 
9393  NOTE: if EpsA,EpsB,EpsC and MaxIts are zero then these variables will
9394  be setted as default values.
9395 
9396  -- ALGLIB --
9397  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
9398  *************************************************************************/
9399  public static void linlsqrsetcond(linlsqrstate state,
9400  double epsa,
9401  double epsb,
9402  int maxits,
9403  alglib.xparams _params)
9404  {
9405  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRSetCond: you can not call this function when LinLSQRIteration is running");
9406  alglib.ap.assert(math.isfinite(epsa) && (double)(epsa)>=(double)(0), "LinLSQRSetCond: EpsA is negative, INF or NAN");
9407  alglib.ap.assert(math.isfinite(epsb) && (double)(epsb)>=(double)(0), "LinLSQRSetCond: EpsB is negative, INF or NAN");
9408  alglib.ap.assert(maxits>=0, "LinLSQRSetCond: MaxIts is negative");
9409  if( ((double)(epsa)==(double)(0) && (double)(epsb)==(double)(0)) && maxits==0 )
9410  {
9411  state.epsa = atol;
9412  state.epsb = btol;
9413  state.maxits = state.n;
9414  }
9415  else
9416  {
9417  state.epsa = epsa;
9418  state.epsb = epsb;
9419  state.maxits = maxits;
9420  }
9421  }
9422 
9423 
9424  /*************************************************************************
9425  LSQR solver: results.
9426 
9427  This function must be called after LinLSQRSolve
9428 
9429  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9430  State - algorithm state
9431 
9432  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
9433  X - array[N], solution
9434  Rep - optimization report:
9435  * Rep.TerminationType completetion code:
9436  * 1 ||Rk||<=EpsB*||B||
9437  * 4 ||A^T*Rk||/(||A||*||Rk||)<=EpsA
9438  * 5 MaxIts steps was taken
9439  * 7 rounding errors prevent further progress,
9440  X contains best point found so far.
9441  (sometimes returned on singular systems)
9442  * 8 user requested termination via calling
9443  linlsqrrequesttermination()
9444  * Rep.IterationsCount contains iterations count
9445  * NMV countains number of matrix-vector calculations
9446 
9447  -- ALGLIB --
9448  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
9449  *************************************************************************/
9450  public static void linlsqrresults(linlsqrstate state,
9451  ref double[] x,
9452  linlsqrreport rep,
9453  alglib.xparams _params)
9454  {
9455  int i_ = 0;
9456 
9457  x = new double[0];
9458 
9459  alglib.ap.assert(!state.running, "LinLSQRResult: you can not call this function when LinLSQRIteration is running");
9460  if( alglib.ap.len(x)<state.n )
9461  {
9462  x = new double[state.n];
9463  }
9464  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
9465  {
9466  x[i_] = state.rx[i_];
9467  }
9468  rep.iterationscount = state.repiterationscount;
9469  rep.nmv = state.repnmv;
9470  rep.terminationtype = state.repterminationtype;
9471  }
9472 
9473 
9474  /*************************************************************************
9475  This function turns on/off reporting.
9476 
9477  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9478  State - structure which stores algorithm state
9479  NeedXRep- whether iteration reports are needed or not
9480 
9481  If NeedXRep is True, algorithm will call rep() callback function if it is
9482  provided to MinCGOptimize().
9483 
9484  -- ALGLIB --
9485  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
9486  *************************************************************************/
9487  public static void linlsqrsetxrep(linlsqrstate state,
9488  bool needxrep,
9489  alglib.xparams _params)
9490  {
9491  state.xrep = needxrep;
9492  }
9493 
9494 
9495  /*************************************************************************
9496  This function restarts LinLSQRIteration
9497 
9498  -- ALGLIB --
9499  Copyright 30.11.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
9500  *************************************************************************/
9501  public static void linlsqrrestart(linlsqrstate state,
9502  alglib.xparams _params)
9503  {
9504  state.rstate.ia = new int[1+1];
9505  state.rstate.ra = new double[0+1];
9506  state.rstate.stage = -1;
9507  clearrfields(state, _params);
9508  state.repiterationscount = 0;
9509  }
9510 
9511 
9512  /*************************************************************************
9513  This function is used to peek into LSQR solver and get current iteration
9514  counter. You can safely "peek" into the solver from another thread.
9515 
9516  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9517  S - solver object
9518 
9519  RESULT:
9520  iteration counter, in [0,INF)
9521 
9522  -- ALGLIB --
9523  Copyright 21.05.2018 by Bochkanov Sergey
9524  *************************************************************************/
9525  public static int linlsqrpeekiterationscount(linlsqrstate s,
9526  alglib.xparams _params)
9527  {
9528  int result = 0;
9529 
9530  result = s.repiterationscount;
9531  return result;
9532  }
9533 
9534 
9535  /*************************************************************************
9536  This subroutine submits request for termination of the running solver. It
9537  can be called from some other thread which wants LSQR solver to terminate
9538  (obviously, the thread running LSQR solver can not request termination
9539  because it is already busy working on LSQR).
9540 
9541  As result, solver stops at point which was "current accepted" when
9542  termination request was submitted and returns error code 8 (successful
9543  termination). Such termination is a smooth process which properly
9544  deallocates all temporaries.
9545 
9546  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9547  State - solver structure
9548 
9549  NOTE: calling this function on solver which is NOT running will have no
9550  effect.
9551 
9552  NOTE: multiple calls to this function are possible. First call is counted,
9553  subsequent calls are silently ignored.
9554 
9555  NOTE: solver clears termination flag on its start, it means that if some
9556  other thread will request termination too soon, its request will went
9557  unnoticed.
9558 
9559  -- ALGLIB --
9560  Copyright 08.10.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
9561  *************************************************************************/
9562  public static void linlsqrrequesttermination(linlsqrstate state,
9563  alglib.xparams _params)
9564  {
9565  state.userterminationneeded = true;
9566  }
9567

9569  /*************************************************************************
9570  Clears request fileds (to be sure that we don't forgot to clear something)
9571  *************************************************************************/
9572  private static void clearrfields(linlsqrstate state,
9573  alglib.xparams _params)
9574  {
9575  state.xupdated = false;
9576  state.needmv = false;
9577  state.needmtv = false;
9578  state.needmv2 = false;
9579  state.needvmv = false;
9580  state.needprec = false;
9581  }

9584  }
9585  public class polynomialsolver
9586  {
9587  public class polynomialsolverreport : apobject
9588  {
9589  public double maxerr;
9590  public polynomialsolverreport()
9591  {
9592  init();
9593  }
9594  public override void init()
9595  {
9596  }
9597  public override alglib.apobject make_copy()
9598  {
9599  polynomialsolverreport _result = new polynomialsolverreport();
9600  _result.maxerr = maxerr;
9601  return _result;
9602  }
9603  };
9604 
9605 
9606 
9607 
9608  /*************************************************************************
9609  Polynomial root finding.
9610 
9611  This function returns all roots of the polynomial
9612  P(x) = a0 + a1*x + a2*x^2 + ... + an*x^n
9613  Both real and complex roots are returned (see below).
9614 
9615  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9616  A - array[N+1], polynomial coefficients:
9617  * A[0] is constant term
9618  * A[N] is a coefficient of X^N
9619  N - polynomial degree
9620 
9621  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
9622  X - array of complex roots:
9623  * for isolated real root, X[I] is strictly real: IMAGE(X[I])=0
9624  * complex roots are always returned in pairs - roots occupy
9625  positions I and I+1, with:
9626  * X[I+1]=Conj(X[I])
9627  * IMAGE(X[I]) > 0
9628  * IMAGE(X[I+1]) = -IMAGE(X[I]) < 0
9629  * multiple real roots may have non-zero imaginary part due
9630  to roundoff errors. There is no reliable way to distinguish
9631  real root of multiplicity 2 from two complex roots in
9632  the presence of roundoff errors.
9633  Rep - report, additional information, following fields are set:
9634  * Rep.MaxErr - max( |P(xi)| ) for i=0..N-1. This field
9635  allows to quickly estimate "quality" of the roots being
9636  returned.
9637 
9638  NOTE: this function uses companion matrix method to find roots. In case
9639  internal EVD solver fails do find eigenvalues, exception is
9640  generated.
9641 
9642  NOTE: roots are not "polished" and no matrix balancing is performed
9643  for them.
9644 
9645  -- ALGLIB --
9646  Copyright 24.02.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
9647  *************************************************************************/
9648  public static void polynomialsolve(double[] a,
9649  int n,
9650  ref complex[] x,
9651  polynomialsolverreport rep,
9652  alglib.xparams _params)
9653  {
9654  double[,] c = new double[0,0];
9655  double[,] vl = new double[0,0];
9656  double[,] vr = new double[0,0];
9657  double[] wr = new double[0];
9658  double[] wi = new double[0];
9659  int i = 0;
9660  int j = 0;
9661  bool status = new bool();
9662  int nz = 0;
9663  int ne = 0;
9664  complex v = 0;
9665  complex vv = 0;
9666 
9667  a = (double[])a.Clone();
9668  x = new complex[0];
9669 
9670  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "PolynomialSolve: N<=0");
9671  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(a)>=n+1, "PolynomialSolve: Length(A)<N+1");
9672  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(a, n+1, _params), "PolynomialSolve: A contains infitite numbers");
9673  alglib.ap.assert((double)(a[n])!=(double)(0), "PolynomialSolve: A[N]=0");
9674 
9675  //
9676  // Prepare
9677  //
9678  x = new complex[n];
9679 
9680  //
9681  // Normalize A:
9682  // * analytically determine NZ zero roots
9683  // * quick exit for NZ=N
9684  // * make residual NE-th degree polynomial monic
9685  // (here NE=N-NZ)
9686  //
9687  nz = 0;
9688  while( nz<n && (double)(a[nz])==(double)(0) )
9689  {
9690  nz = nz+1;
9691  }
9692  ne = n-nz;
9693  for(i=nz; i<=n; i++)
9694  {
9695  a[i-nz] = a[i]/a[n];
9696  }
9697 
9698  //
9699  // For NZ<N, build companion matrix and find NE non-zero roots
9700  //
9701  if( ne>0 )
9702  {
9703  c = new double[ne, ne];
9704  for(i=0; i<=ne-1; i++)
9705  {
9706  for(j=0; j<=ne-1; j++)
9707  {
9708  c[i,j] = 0;
9709  }
9710  }
9711  c[0,ne-1] = -a[0];
9712  for(i=1; i<=ne-1; i++)
9713  {
9714  c[i,i-1] = 1;
9715  c[i,ne-1] = -a[i];
9716  }
9717  status = evd.rmatrixevd(c, ne, 0, ref wr, ref wi, ref vl, ref vr, _params);
9718  alglib.ap.assert(status, "PolynomialSolve: inernal error - EVD solver failed");
9719  for(i=0; i<=ne-1; i++)
9720  {
9721  x[i].x = wr[i];
9722  x[i].y = wi[i];
9723  }
9724  }
9725 
9726  //
9727  // Remaining NZ zero roots
9728  //
9729  for(i=ne; i<=n-1; i++)
9730  {
9731  x[i] = 0;
9732  }
9733 
9734  //
9735  // Rep
9736  //
9737  rep.maxerr = 0;
9738  for(i=0; i<=ne-1; i++)
9739  {
9740  v = 0;
9741  vv = 1;
9742  for(j=0; j<=ne; j++)
9743  {
9744  v = v+a[j]*vv;
9745  vv = vv*x[i];
9746  }
9747  rep.maxerr = Math.Max(rep.maxerr, math.abscomplex(v));
9748  }
9749  }
9750 
9751 
9752  }
9753  public class nleq
9754  {
9755  public class nleqstate : apobject
9756  {
9757  public int n;
9758  public int m;
9759  public double epsf;
9760  public int maxits;
9761  public bool xrep;
9762  public double stpmax;
9763  public double[] x;
9764  public double f;
9765  public double[] fi;
9766  public double[,] j;
9767  public bool needf;
9768  public bool needfij;
9769  public bool xupdated;
9770  public rcommstate rstate;
9771  public int repiterationscount;
9772  public int repnfunc;
9773  public int repnjac;
9774  public int repterminationtype;
9775  public double[] xbase;
9776  public double fbase;
9777  public double fprev;
9778  public double[] candstep;
9779  public double[] rightpart;
9780  public double[] cgbuf;
9781  public nleqstate()
9782  {
9783  init();
9784  }
9785  public override void init()
9786  {
9787  x = new double[0];
9788  fi = new double[0];
9789  j = new double[0,0];
9790  rstate = new rcommstate();
9791  xbase = new double[0];
9792  candstep = new double[0];
9793  rightpart = new double[0];
9794  cgbuf = new double[0];
9795  }
9796  public override alglib.apobject make_copy()
9797  {
9798  nleqstate _result = new nleqstate();
9799  _result.n = n;
9800  _result.m = m;
9801  _result.epsf = epsf;
9802  _result.maxits = maxits;
9803  _result.xrep = xrep;
9804  _result.stpmax = stpmax;
9805  _result.x = (double[])x.Clone();
9806  _result.f = f;
9807  _result.fi = (double[])fi.Clone();
9808  _result.j = (double[,])j.Clone();
9809  _result.needf = needf;
9810  _result.needfij = needfij;
9811  _result.xupdated = xupdated;
9812  _result.rstate = (rcommstate)rstate.make_copy();
9813  _result.repiterationscount = repiterationscount;
9814  _result.repnfunc = repnfunc;
9815  _result.repnjac = repnjac;
9816  _result.repterminationtype = repterminationtype;
9817  _result.xbase = (double[])xbase.Clone();
9818  _result.fbase = fbase;
9819  _result.fprev = fprev;
9820  _result.candstep = (double[])candstep.Clone();
9821  _result.rightpart = (double[])rightpart.Clone();
9822  _result.cgbuf = (double[])cgbuf.Clone();
9823  return _result;
9824  }
9825  };

9828  public class nleqreport : apobject
9829  {
9830  public int iterationscount;
9831  public int nfunc;
9832  public int njac;
9833  public int terminationtype;
9834  public nleqreport()
9835  {
9836  init();
9837  }
9838  public override void init()
9839  {
9840  }
9841  public override alglib.apobject make_copy()
9842  {
9843  nleqreport _result = new nleqreport();
9844  _result.iterationscount = iterationscount;
9845  _result.nfunc = nfunc;
9846  _result.njac = njac;
9847  _result.terminationtype = terminationtype;
9848  return _result;
9849  }
9850  };
9851 
9852 
9853 
9854 
9855  /*************************************************************************
9856  LEVENBERG-MARQUARDT-LIKE NONLINEAR SOLVER
9857 
9858  DESCRIPTION:
9859  This algorithm solves system of nonlinear equations
9860  F[0](x[0], ..., x[n-1]) = 0
9861  F[1](x[0], ..., x[n-1]) = 0
9862  ...
9863  F[M-1](x[0], ..., x[n-1]) = 0
9864  with M/N do not necessarily coincide. Algorithm converges quadratically
9865  under following conditions:
9866  * the solution set XS is nonempty
9867  * for some xs in XS there exist such neighbourhood N(xs) that:
9868  * vector function F(x) and its Jacobian J(x) are continuously
9869  differentiable on N
9870  * ||F(x)|| provides local error bound on N, i.e. there exists such
9871  c1, that ||F(x)||>c1*distance(x,XS)
9872  Note that these conditions are much more weaker than usual non-singularity
9873  conditions. For example, algorithm will converge for any affine function
9874  F (whether its Jacobian singular or not).
9875 
9876 
9877  REQUIREMENTS:
9878  Algorithm will request following information during its operation:
9879  * function vector F[] and Jacobian matrix at given point X
9880  * value of merit function f(x)=F[0]^2(x)+...+F[M-1]^2(x) at given point X
9881 
9882 
9883  USAGE:
9884  1. User initializes algorithm state with NLEQCreateLM() call
9885  2. User tunes solver parameters with NLEQSetCond(), NLEQSetStpMax() and
9886  other functions
9887  3. User calls NLEQSolve() function which takes algorithm state and
9888  pointers (delegates, etc.) to callback functions which calculate merit
9889  function value and Jacobian.
9890  4. User calls NLEQResults() to get solution
9891  5. Optionally, user may call NLEQRestartFrom() to solve another problem
9892  with same parameters (N/M) but another starting point and/or another
9893  function vector. NLEQRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized
9894  structure.
9895 
9896 
9897  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9898  N - space dimension, N>1:
9899  * if provided, only leading N elements of X are used
9900  * if not provided, determined automatically from size of X
9901  M - system size
9902  X - starting point
9903 
9904 
9905  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
9906  State - structure which stores algorithm state
9907 
9908 
9909  NOTES:
9910  1. you may tune stopping conditions with NLEQSetCond() function
9911  2. if target function contains exp() or other fast growing functions, and
9912  optimization algorithm makes too large steps which leads to overflow,
9913  use NLEQSetStpMax() function to bound algorithm's steps.
9914  3. this algorithm is a slightly modified implementation of the method
9915  described in 'Levenberg-Marquardt method for constrained nonlinear
9916  equations with strong local convergence properties' by Christian Kanzow
9917  Nobuo Yamashita and Masao Fukushima and further developed in 'On the
9918  convergence of a New Levenberg-Marquardt Method' by Jin-yan Fan and
9919  Ya-Xiang Yuan.
9920 
9921 
9922  -- ALGLIB --
9923  Copyright 20.08.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
9924  *************************************************************************/
9925  public static void nleqcreatelm(int n,
9926  int m,
9927  double[] x,
9928  nleqstate state,
9929  alglib.xparams _params)
9930  {
9931  alglib.ap.assert(n>=1, "NLEQCreateLM: N<1!");
9932  alglib.ap.assert(m>=1, "NLEQCreateLM: M<1!");
9933  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(x)>=n, "NLEQCreateLM: Length(X)<N!");
9934  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(x, n, _params), "NLEQCreateLM: X contains infinite or NaN values!");
9935 
9936  //
9937  // Initialize
9938  //
9939  state.n = n;
9940  state.m = m;
9941  nleqsetcond(state, 0, 0, _params);
9942  nleqsetxrep(state, false, _params);
9943  nleqsetstpmax(state, 0, _params);
9944  state.x = new double[n];
9945  state.xbase = new double[n];
9946  state.j = new double[m, n];
9947  state.fi = new double[m];
9948  state.rightpart = new double[n];
9949  state.candstep = new double[n];
9950  nleqrestartfrom(state, x, _params);
9951  }
9952 
9953 
9954  /*************************************************************************
9955  This function sets stopping conditions for the nonlinear solver
9956 
9957  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9958  State - structure which stores algorithm state
9959  EpsF - >=0
9960  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
9961  the condition ||F||<=EpsF is satisfied
9962  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
9963  iterations is unlimited.
9964 
9965  Passing EpsF=0 and MaxIts=0 simultaneously will lead to automatic
9966  stopping criterion selection (small EpsF).
9967 
9968  NOTES:
9969 
9970  -- ALGLIB --
9971  Copyright 20.08.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
9972  *************************************************************************/
9973  public static void nleqsetcond(nleqstate state,
9974  double epsf,
9975  int maxits,
9976  alglib.xparams _params)
9977  {
9978  alglib.ap.assert(math.isfinite(epsf), "NLEQSetCond: EpsF is not finite number!");
9979  alglib.ap.assert((double)(epsf)>=(double)(0), "NLEQSetCond: negative EpsF!");
9980  alglib.ap.assert(maxits>=0, "NLEQSetCond: negative MaxIts!");
9981  if( (double)(epsf)==(double)(0) && maxits==0 )
9982  {
9983  epsf = 1.0E-6;
9984  }
9985  state.epsf = epsf;
9986  state.maxits = maxits;
9987  }
9988 
9989 
9990  /*************************************************************************
9991  This function turns on/off reporting.
9992 
9993  INPUT PARAMETERS:
9994  State - structure which stores algorithm state
9995  NeedXRep- whether iteration reports are needed or not
9996 
9997  If NeedXRep is True, algorithm will call rep() callback function if it is
9998  provided to NLEQSolve().
9999 
10000  -- ALGLIB --
10001  Copyright 20.08.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
10002  *************************************************************************/
10003  public static void nleqsetxrep(nleqstate state,
10004  bool needxrep,
10005  alglib.xparams _params)
10006  {
10007  state.xrep = needxrep;
10008  }
10009 
10010 
10011  /*************************************************************************
10012  This function sets maximum step length
10013 
10014  INPUT PARAMETERS:
10015  State - structure which stores algorithm state
10016  StpMax - maximum step length, >=0. Set StpMax to 0.0, if you don't
10017  want to limit step length.
10018 
10019  Use this subroutine when target function contains exp() or other fast
10020  growing functions, and algorithm makes too large steps which lead to
10021  overflow. This function allows us to reject steps that are too large (and
10022  therefore expose us to the possible overflow) without actually calculating
10023  function value at the x+stp*d.
10024 
10025  -- ALGLIB --
10026  Copyright 20.08.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
10027  *************************************************************************/
10028  public static void nleqsetstpmax(nleqstate state,
10029  double stpmax,
10030  alglib.xparams _params)
10031  {
10032  alglib.ap.assert(math.isfinite(stpmax), "NLEQSetStpMax: StpMax is not finite!");
10033  alglib.ap.assert((double)(stpmax)>=(double)(0), "NLEQSetStpMax: StpMax<0!");
10034  state.stpmax = stpmax;
10035  }
10036 
10037 
10038  /*************************************************************************
10039 
10040  -- ALGLIB --
10041  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
10042  *************************************************************************/
10043  public static bool nleqiteration(nleqstate state,
10044  alglib.xparams _params)
10045  {
10046  bool result = new bool();
10047  int n = 0;
10048  int m = 0;
10049  int i = 0;
10050  double lambdaup = 0;
10051  double lambdadown = 0;
10052  double lambdav = 0;
10053  double rho = 0;
10054  double mu = 0;
10055  double stepnorm = 0;
10056  bool b = new bool();
10057  int i_ = 0;
10058 
10059 
10060  //
10061  // Reverse communication preparations
10062  // I know it looks ugly, but it works the same way
10063  // anywhere from C++ to Python.
10064  //
10065  // This code initializes locals by:
10066  // * random values determined during code
10067  // generation - on first subroutine call
10068  // * values from previous call - on subsequent calls
10069  //
10070  if( state.rstate.stage>=0 )
10071  {
10072  n = state.rstate.ia[0];
10073  m = state.rstate.ia[1];
10074  i = state.rstate.ia[2];
10075  b = state.rstate.ba[0];
10076  lambdaup = state.rstate.ra[0];
10077  lambdadown = state.rstate.ra[1];
10078  lambdav = state.rstate.ra[2];
10079  rho = state.rstate.ra[3];
10080  mu = state.rstate.ra[4];
10081  stepnorm = state.rstate.ra[5];
10082  }
10083  else
10084  {
10085  n = 359;
10086  m = -58;
10087  i = -919;
10088  b = true;
10089  lambdaup = 81;
10090  lambdadown = 255;
10091  lambdav = 74;
10092  rho = -788;
10093  mu = 809;
10094  stepnorm = 205;
10095  }
10096  if( state.rstate.stage==0 )
10097  {
10098  goto lbl_0;
10099  }
10100  if( state.rstate.stage==1 )
10101  {
10102  goto lbl_1;
10103  }
10104  if( state.rstate.stage==2 )
10105  {
10106  goto lbl_2;
10107  }
10108  if( state.rstate.stage==3 )
10109  {
10110  goto lbl_3;
10111  }
10112  if( state.rstate.stage==4 )
10113  {
10114  goto lbl_4;
10115  }
10116 
10117  //
10118  // Routine body
10119  //
10120 
10121  //
10122  // Prepare
10123  //
10124  n = state.n;
10125  m = state.m;
10126  state.repterminationtype = 0;
10127  state.repiterationscount = 0;
10128  state.repnfunc = 0;
10129  state.repnjac = 0;
10130 
10131  //
10132  // Calculate F/G, initialize algorithm
10133  //
10134  clearrequestfields(state, _params);
10135  state.needf = true;
10136  state.rstate.stage = 0;
10137  goto lbl_rcomm;
10138  lbl_0:
10139  state.needf = false;
10140  state.repnfunc = state.repnfunc+1;
10141  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10142  {
10143  state.xbase[i_] = state.x[i_];
10144  }
10145  state.fbase = state.f;
10146  state.fprev = math.maxrealnumber;
10147  if( !state.xrep )
10148  {
10149  goto lbl_5;
10150  }
10151 
10152  //
10153  // progress report
10154  //
10155  clearrequestfields(state, _params);
10156  state.xupdated = true;
10157  state.rstate.stage = 1;
10158  goto lbl_rcomm;
10159  lbl_1:
10160  state.xupdated = false;
10161  lbl_5:
10162  if( (double)(state.f)<=(double)(math.sqr(state.epsf)) )
10163  {
10164  state.repterminationtype = 1;
10165  result = false;
10166  return result;
10167  }
10168 
10169  //
10170  // Main cycle
10171  //
10172  lambdaup = 10;
10173  lambdadown = 0.3;
10174  lambdav = 0.001;
10175  rho = 1;
10176  lbl_7:
10177  if( false )
10178  {
10179  goto lbl_8;
10180  }
10181 
10182  //
10183  // Get Jacobian;
10184  // before we get to this point we already have State.XBase filled
10185  // with current point and State.FBase filled with function value
10186  // at XBase
10187  //
10188  clearrequestfields(state, _params);
10189  state.needfij = true;
10190  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10191  {
10192  state.x[i_] = state.xbase[i_];
10193  }
10194  state.rstate.stage = 2;
10195  goto lbl_rcomm;
10196  lbl_2:
10197  state.needfij = false;
10198  state.repnfunc = state.repnfunc+1;
10199  state.repnjac = state.repnjac+1;
10200  ablas.rmatrixmv(n, m, state.j, 0, 0, 1, state.fi, 0, state.rightpart, 0, _params);
10201  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10202  {
10203  state.rightpart[i_] = -1*state.rightpart[i_];
10204  }
10205 
10206  //
10207  // Inner cycle: find good lambda
10208  //
10209  lbl_9:
10210  if( false )
10211  {
10212  goto lbl_10;
10213  }
10214 
10215  //
10216  // Solve (J^T*J + (Lambda+Mu)*I)*y = J^T*F
10217  // to get step d=-y where:
10218  // * Mu=||F|| - is damping parameter for nonlinear system
10219  // * Lambda - is additional Levenberg-Marquardt parameter
10220  // for better convergence when far away from minimum
10221  //
10222  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10223  {
10224  state.candstep[i] = 0;
10225  }
10226  fbls.fblssolvecgx(state.j, m, n, lambdav, state.rightpart, ref state.candstep, ref state.cgbuf, _params);
10227 
10228  //
10229  // Normalize step (it must be no more than StpMax)
10230  //
10231  stepnorm = 0;
10232  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10233  {
10234  if( (double)(state.candstep[i])!=(double)(0) )
10235  {
10236  stepnorm = 1;
10237  break;
10238  }
10239  }
10240  linmin.linminnormalized(ref state.candstep, ref stepnorm, n, _params);
10241  if( (double)(state.stpmax)!=(double)(0) )
10242  {
10243  stepnorm = Math.Min(stepnorm, state.stpmax);
10244  }
10245 
10246  //
10247  // Test new step - is it good enough?
10248  // * if not, Lambda is increased and we try again.
10249  // * if step is good, we decrease Lambda and move on.
10250  //
10251  // We can break this cycle on two occasions:
10252  // * step is so small that x+step==x (in floating point arithmetics)
10253  // * lambda is so large
10254  //
10255  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10256  {
10257  state.x[i_] = state.xbase[i_];
10258  }
10259  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10260  {
10261  state.x[i_] = state.x[i_] + stepnorm*state.candstep[i_];
10262  }
10263  b = true;
10264  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10265  {
10266  if( (double)(state.x[i])!=(double)(state.xbase[i]) )
10267  {
10268  b = false;
10269  break;
10270  }
10271  }
10272  if( b )
10273  {
10274 
10275  //
10276  // Step is too small, force zero step and break
10277  //
10278  stepnorm = 0;
10279  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10280  {
10281  state.x[i_] = state.xbase[i_];
10282  }
10283  state.f = state.fbase;
10284  goto lbl_10;
10285  }
10286  clearrequestfields(state, _params);
10287  state.needf = true;
10288  state.rstate.stage = 3;
10289  goto lbl_rcomm;
10290  lbl_3:
10291  state.needf = false;
10292  state.repnfunc = state.repnfunc+1;
10293  if( (double)(state.f)<(double)(state.fbase) )
10294  {
10295 
10296  //
10297  // function value decreased, move on
10298  //
10299  decreaselambda(ref lambdav, ref rho, lambdadown, _params);
10300  goto lbl_10;
10301  }
10302  if( !increaselambda(ref lambdav, ref rho, lambdaup, _params) )
10303  {
10304 
10305  //
10306  // Lambda is too large (near overflow), force zero step and break
10307  //
10308  stepnorm = 0;
10309  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10310  {
10311  state.x[i_] = state.xbase[i_];
10312  }
10313  state.f = state.fbase;
10314  goto lbl_10;
10315  }
10316  goto lbl_9;
10317  lbl_10:
10318 
10319  //
10320  // Accept step:
10321  // * new position
10322  // * new function value
10323  //
10324  state.fbase = state.f;
10325  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10326  {
10327  state.xbase[i_] = state.xbase[i_] + stepnorm*state.candstep[i_];
10328  }
10329  state.repiterationscount = state.repiterationscount+1;
10330 
10331  //
10332  // Report new iteration
10333  //
10334  if( !state.xrep )
10335  {
10336  goto lbl_11;
10337  }
10338  clearrequestfields(state, _params);
10339  state.xupdated = true;
10340  state.f = state.fbase;
10341  for(i_=0; i_<=n-1;i_++)
10342  {
10343  state.x[i_] = state.xbase[i_];
10344  }
10345  state.rstate.stage = 4;
10346  goto lbl_rcomm;
10347  lbl_4:
10348  state.xupdated = false;
10349  lbl_11:
10350 
10351  //
10352  // Test stopping conditions on F, step (zero/non-zero) and MaxIts;
10353  // If one of the conditions is met, RepTerminationType is changed.
10354  //
10355  if( (double)(Math.Sqrt(state.f))<=(double)(state.epsf) )
10356  {
10357  state.repterminationtype = 1;
10358  }
10359  if( (double)(stepnorm)==(double)(0) && state.repterminationtype==0 )
10360  {
10361  state.repterminationtype = -4;
10362  }
10363  if( state.repiterationscount>=state.maxits && state.maxits>0 )
10364  {
10365  state.repterminationtype = 5;
10366  }
10367  if( state.repterminationtype!=0 )
10368  {
10369  goto lbl_8;
10370  }
10371 
10372  //
10373  // Now, iteration is finally over
10374  //
10375  goto lbl_7;
10376  lbl_8:
10377  result = false;
10378  return result;
10379 
10380  //
10381  // Saving state
10382  //
10383  lbl_rcomm:
10384  result = true;
10385  state.rstate.ia[0] = n;
10386  state.rstate.ia[1] = m;
10387  state.rstate.ia[2] = i;
10388  state.rstate.ba[0] = b;
10389  state.rstate.ra[0] = lambdaup;
10390  state.rstate.ra[1] = lambdadown;
10391  state.rstate.ra[2] = lambdav;
10392  state.rstate.ra[3] = rho;
10393  state.rstate.ra[4] = mu;
10394  state.rstate.ra[5] = stepnorm;
10395  return result;
10396  }
10397 
10398 
10399  /*************************************************************************
10400  NLEQ solver results
10401 
10402  INPUT PARAMETERS:
10403  State - algorithm state.
10404 
10405  OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
10406  X - array[0..N-1], solution
10407  Rep - optimization report:
10408  * Rep.TerminationType completetion code:
10409  * -4 ERROR: algorithm has converged to the
10410  stationary point Xf which is local minimum of
10411  f=F[0]^2+...+F[m-1]^2, but is not solution of
10412  nonlinear system.
10413  * 1 sqrt(f)<=EpsF.
10414  * 5 MaxIts steps was taken
10415  * 7 stopping conditions are too stringent,
10416  further improvement is impossible
10417  * Rep.IterationsCount contains iterations count
10418  * NFEV countains number of function calculations
10419  * ActiveConstraints contains number of active constraints
10420 
10421  -- ALGLIB --
10422  Copyright 20.08.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
10423  *************************************************************************/
10424  public static void nleqresults(nleqstate state,
10425  ref double[] x,
10426  nleqreport rep,
10427  alglib.xparams _params)
10428  {
10429  x = new double[0];
10430 
10431  nleqresultsbuf(state, ref x, rep, _params);
10432  }
10433 
10434 
10435  /*************************************************************************
10436  NLEQ solver results
10437 
10438  Buffered implementation of NLEQResults(), which uses pre-allocated buffer
10439  to store X[]. If buffer size is too small, it resizes buffer. It is
10440  intended to be used in the inner cycles of performance critical algorithms
10441  where array reallocation penalty is too large to be ignored.
10442 
10443  -- ALGLIB --
10444  Copyright 20.08.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
10445  *************************************************************************/
10446  public static void nleqresultsbuf(nleqstate state,
10447  ref double[] x,
10448  nleqreport rep,
10449  alglib.xparams _params)
10450  {
10451  int i_ = 0;
10452 
10453  if( alglib.ap.len(x)<state.n )
10454  {
10455  x = new double[state.n];
10456  }
10457  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
10458  {
10459  x[i_] = state.xbase[i_];
10460  }
10461  rep.iterationscount = state.repiterationscount;
10462  rep.nfunc = state.repnfunc;
10463  rep.njac = state.repnjac;
10464  rep.terminationtype = state.repterminationtype;
10465  }
10466 
10467 
10468  /*************************************************************************
10469  This subroutine restarts CG algorithm from new point. All optimization
10470  parameters are left unchanged.
10471 
10472  This function allows to solve multiple optimization problems (which
10473  must have same number of dimensions) without object reallocation penalty.
10474 
10475  INPUT PARAMETERS:
10476  State - structure used for reverse communication previously
10477  allocated with MinCGCreate call.
10478  X - new starting point.
10479  BndL - new lower bounds
10480  BndU - new upper bounds
10481 
10482  -- ALGLIB --
10483  Copyright 30.07.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
10484  *************************************************************************/
10485  public static void nleqrestartfrom(nleqstate state,
10486  double[] x,
10487  alglib.xparams _params)
10488  {
10489  int i_ = 0;
10490 
10491  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(x)>=state.n, "NLEQRestartFrom: Length(X)<N!");
10492  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(x, state.n, _params), "NLEQRestartFrom: X contains infinite or NaN values!");
10493  for(i_=0; i_<=state.n-1;i_++)
10494  {
10495  state.x[i_] = x[i_];
10496  }
10497  state.rstate.ia = new int[2+1];
10498  state.rstate.ba = new bool[0+1];
10499  state.rstate.ra = new double[5+1];
10500  state.rstate.stage = -1;
10501  clearrequestfields(state, _params);
10502  }
10503 
10504 
10505  /*************************************************************************
10506  Clears request fileds (to be sure that we don't forgot to clear something)
10507  *************************************************************************/
10508  private static void clearrequestfields(nleqstate state,
10509  alglib.xparams _params)
10510  {
10511  state.needf = false;
10512  state.needfij = false;
10513  state.xupdated = false;
10514  }

10516 
10517  /*************************************************************************
10518  Increases lambda, returns False when there is a danger of overflow
10519  *************************************************************************/
10520  private static bool increaselambda(ref double lambdav,
10521  ref double nu,
10522  double lambdaup,
10523  alglib.xparams _params)
10524  {
10525  bool result = new bool();
10526  double lnlambda = 0;
10527  double lnnu = 0;
10528  double lnlambdaup = 0;
10529  double lnmax = 0;
10530 
10531  result = false;
10532  lnlambda = Math.Log(lambdav);
10533  lnlambdaup = Math.Log(lambdaup);
10534  lnnu = Math.Log(nu);
10535  lnmax = 0.5*Math.Log(math.maxrealnumber);
10536  if( (double)(lnlambda+lnlambdaup+lnnu)>(double)(lnmax) )
10537  {
10538  return result;
10539  }
10540  if( (double)(lnnu+Math.Log(2))>(double)(lnmax) )
10541  {
10542  return result;
10543  }
10544  lambdav = lambdav*lambdaup*nu;
10545  nu = nu*2;
10546  result = true;
10547  return result;
10548  }
10549 
10550 
10551  /*************************************************************************
10552  Decreases lambda, but leaves it unchanged when there is danger of underflow.
10553  *************************************************************************/
10554  private static void decreaselambda(ref double lambdav,
10555  ref double nu,
10556  double lambdadown,
10557  alglib.xparams _params)
10558  {
10559  nu = 1;
10560  if( (double)(Math.Log(lambdav)+Math.Log(lambdadown))<(double)(Math.Log(math.minrealnumber)) )
10561  {
10562  lambdav = math.minrealnumber;
10563  }
10564  else
10565  {
10566  lambdav = lambdav*lambdadown;
10567  }
10568  }

10571  }
10572  public class directsparsesolvers
10573  {

10575  This structure is a sparse solver report.
10576

10578  *************************************************************************/
10579  public class sparsesolverreport : apobject
10580  {

10582  public sparsesolverreport()

10585  }

10587  {
10588  }
10589  public override alglib.apobject make_copy()

10596 
10597 
10598 
10599 
10600  /*************************************************************************
10601  Sparse linear solver for A*x=b with N*N sparse real symmetric positive
10602  definite matrix A, N*1 vectors x and b.
10603 
10604  This solver converts input matrix to SKS format, performs Cholesky
10605  factorization using SKS Cholesky subroutine (works well for limited
10606  bandwidth matrices) and uses sparse triangular solvers to get solution of
10607  the original system.
10608 
10609  INPUT PARAMETERS
10610  A - sparse matrix, must be NxN exactly
10611  N - size of A, N>0
10612  IsUpper - which half of A is provided (another half is ignored)
10613  B - array[0..N-1], right part
10614 
10615  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
10616  Rep - solver report, following fields are set:
10617  * rep.terminationtype - solver status; >0 for success,
10618  set to -3 on failure (degenerate or non-SPD system).
10619  X - array[N], it contains:
10620  * rep.terminationtype>0 => solution
10621  * rep.terminationtype=-3 => filled by zeros
10622 
10623  -- ALGLIB --
10624  Copyright 26.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
10625  *************************************************************************/
10626  public static void sparsesolvesks(sparse.sparsematrix a,
10627  int n,
10628  bool isupper,
10629  double[] b,
10630  sparsesolverreport rep,
10631  ref double[] x,
10632  alglib.xparams _params)
10633  {
10634  int i = 0;
10635  sparse.sparsematrix a2 = new sparse.sparsematrix();
10636 
10637  x = new double[0];
10638 
10639  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "SparseSolveSKS: N<=0");
10640  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetnrows(a, _params)==n, "SparseSolveSKS: rows(A)!=N");
10641  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetncols(a, _params)==n, "SparseSolveSKS: cols(A)!=N");
10642  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(b)>=n, "SparseSolveSKS: length(B)<N");
10643  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(b, n, _params), "SparseSolveSKS: B contains infinities or NANs");
10644  initreport(rep, _params);
10645  x = new double[n];
10646  sparse.sparsecopytosks(a, a2, _params);
10647  if( !trfac.sparsecholeskyskyline(a2, n, isupper, _params) )
10648  {
10649  rep.terminationtype = -3;
10650  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10651  {
10652  x[i] = 0;
10653  }
10654  return;
10655  }
10656  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10657  {
10658  x[i] = b[i];
10659  }
10660  if( isupper )
10661  {
10662  sparse.sparsetrsv(a2, isupper, false, 1, x, _params);
10663  sparse.sparsetrsv(a2, isupper, false, 0, x, _params);
10664  }
10665  else
10666  {
10667  sparse.sparsetrsv(a2, isupper, false, 0, x, _params);
10668  sparse.sparsetrsv(a2, isupper, false, 1, x, _params);
10669  }
10670  rep.terminationtype = 1;
10671  }
10672 
10673 
10674  /*************************************************************************
10675  Sparse linear solver for A*x=b with N*N real symmetric positive definite
10676  matrix A given by its Cholesky decomposition, and N*1 vectors x and b.
10677 
10678  IMPORTANT: this solver requires input matrix to be in the SKS (Skyline)
10679  sparse storage format. An exception will be generated if you
10680  pass matrix in some other format (HASH or CRS).
10681 
10682  INPUT PARAMETERS
10683  A - sparse NxN matrix stored in SKS format, must be NxN exactly
10684  N - size of A, N>0
10685  IsUpper - which half of A is provided (another half is ignored)
10686  B - array[N], right part
10687 
10688  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
10689  Rep - solver report, following fields are set:
10690  * rep.terminationtype - solver status; >0 for success,
10691  set to -3 on failure (degenerate or non-SPD system).
10692  X - array[N], it contains:
10693  * rep.terminationtype>0 => solution
10694  * rep.terminationtype=-3 => filled by zeros
10695 
10696  -- ALGLIB --
10697  Copyright 26.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
10698  *************************************************************************/
10699  public static void sparsecholeskysolvesks(sparse.sparsematrix a,
10700  int n,
10701  bool isupper,
10702  double[] b,
10703  sparsesolverreport rep,
10704  ref double[] x,
10705  alglib.xparams _params)
10706  {
10707  int i = 0;
10708 
10709  x = new double[0];
10710 
10711  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "SparseSolveSKS: N<=0");
10712  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetnrows(a, _params)==n, "SparseSolveSKS: rows(A)!=N");
10713  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetncols(a, _params)==n, "SparseSolveSKS: cols(A)!=N");
10714  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparseissks(a, _params), "SparseSolveSKS: A is not an SKS matrix");
10715  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(b)>=n, "SparseSolveSKS: length(B)<N");
10716  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(b, n, _params), "SparseSolveSKS: B contains infinities or NANs");
10717  initreport(rep, _params);
10718  x = new double[n];
10719  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10720  {
10721  if( (double)(sparse.sparseget(a, i, i, _params))==(double)(0.0) )
10722  {
10723  rep.terminationtype = -3;
10724  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10725  {
10726  x[i] = 0;
10727  }
10728  return;
10729  }
10730  }
10731  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10732  {
10733  x[i] = b[i];
10734  }
10735  if( isupper )
10736  {
10737  sparse.sparsetrsv(a, isupper, false, 1, x, _params);
10738  sparse.sparsetrsv(a, isupper, false, 0, x, _params);
10739  }
10740  else
10741  {
10742  sparse.sparsetrsv(a, isupper, false, 0, x, _params);
10743  sparse.sparsetrsv(a, isupper, false, 1, x, _params);
10744  }
10745  rep.terminationtype = 1;
10746  }
10747 
10748 
10749  /*************************************************************************
10750  Sparse linear solver for A*x=b with general (nonsymmetric) N*N sparse real
10751  matrix A, N*1 vectors x and b.
10752 
10753  This solver converts input matrix to CRS format, performs LU factorization
10754  and uses sparse triangular solvers to get solution of the original system.
10755 
10756  INPUT PARAMETERS
10757  A - sparse matrix, must be NxN exactly, any storage format
10758  N - size of A, N>0
10759  B - array[0..N-1], right part
10760 
10761  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
10762  X - array[N], it contains:
10763  * rep.terminationtype>0 => solution
10764  * rep.terminationtype=-3 => filled by zeros
10765  Rep - solver report, following fields are set:
10766  * rep.terminationtype - solver status; >0 for success,
10767  set to -3 on failure (degenerate system).
10768 
10769  -- ALGLIB --
10770  Copyright 26.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
10771  *************************************************************************/
10772  public static void sparsesolve(sparse.sparsematrix a,
10773  int n,
10774  double[] b,
10775  ref double[] x,
10776  sparsesolverreport rep,
10777  alglib.xparams _params)
10778  {
10779  int i = 0;
10780  int j = 0;
10781  double v = 0;
10782  sparse.sparsematrix a2 = new sparse.sparsematrix();
10783  int[] pivp = new int[0];
10784  int[] pivq = new int[0];
10785 
10786  x = new double[0];
10787 
10788  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "SparseSolve: N<=0");
10789  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetnrows(a, _params)==n, "SparseSolve: rows(A)!=N");
10790  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetncols(a, _params)==n, "SparseSolve: cols(A)!=N");
10791  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(b)>=n, "SparseSolve: length(B)<N");
10792  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(b, n, _params), "SparseSolve: B contains infinities or NANs");
10793  initreport(rep, _params);
10794  x = new double[n];
10795  sparse.sparsecopytocrs(a, a2, _params);
10796  if( !trfac.sparselu(a2, 0, ref pivp, ref pivq, _params) )
10797  {
10798  rep.terminationtype = -3;
10799  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10800  {
10801  x[i] = 0;
10802  }
10803  return;
10804  }
10805  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10806  {
10807  x[i] = b[i];
10808  }
10809  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10810  {
10811  j = pivp[i];
10812  v = x[i];
10813  x[i] = x[j];
10814  x[j] = v;
10815  }
10816  sparse.sparsetrsv(a2, false, true, 0, x, _params);
10817  sparse.sparsetrsv(a2, true, false, 0, x, _params);
10818  for(i=n-1; i>=0; i--)
10819  {
10820  j = pivq[i];
10821  v = x[i];
10822  x[i] = x[j];
10823  x[j] = v;
10824  }
10825  rep.terminationtype = 1;
10826  }
10827 
10828 
10829  /*************************************************************************
10830  Sparse linear solver for A*x=b with general (nonsymmetric) N*N sparse real
10831  matrix A given by its LU factorization, N*1 vectors x and b.
10832 
10833  IMPORTANT: this solver requires input matrix to be in the CRS sparse
10834  storage format. An exception will be generated if you pass
10835  matrix in some other format (HASH or SKS).
10836 
10837  INPUT PARAMETERS
10838  A - LU factorization of the sparse matrix, must be NxN exactly
10839  in CRS storage format
10840  P, Q - pivot indexes from LU factorization
10841  N - size of A, N>0
10842  B - array[0..N-1], right part
10843 
10844  OUTPUT PARAMETERS
10845  X - array[N], it contains:
10846  * rep.terminationtype>0 => solution
10847  * rep.terminationtype=-3 => filled by zeros
10848  Rep - solver report, following fields are set:
10849  * rep.terminationtype - solver status; >0 for success,
10850  set to -3 on failure (degenerate system).
10851 
10852  -- ALGLIB --
10853  Copyright 26.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
10854  *************************************************************************/
10855  public static void sparselusolve(sparse.sparsematrix a,
10856  int[] p,
10857  int[] q,
10858  int n,
10859  double[] b,
10860  ref double[] x,
10861  sparsesolverreport rep,
10862  alglib.xparams _params)
10863  {
10864  int i = 0;
10865  int j = 0;
10866  double v = 0;
10867 
10868  x = new double[0];
10869 
10870  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "SparseLUSolve: N<=0");
10871  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetnrows(a, _params)==n, "SparseLUSolve: rows(A)!=N");
10872  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparsegetncols(a, _params)==n, "SparseLUSolve: cols(A)!=N");
10873  alglib.ap.assert(sparse.sparseiscrs(a, _params), "SparseLUSolve: A is not an SKS matrix");
10874  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(b)>=n, "SparseLUSolve: length(B)<N");
10875  alglib.ap.assert(apserv.isfinitevector(b, n, _params), "SparseLUSolve: B contains infinities or NANs");
10876  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(p)>=n, "SparseLUSolve: length(P)<N");
10877  alglib.ap.assert(alglib.ap.len(q)>=n, "SparseLUSolve: length(Q)<N");
10878  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10879  {
10880  alglib.ap.assert(p[i]>=i && p[i]<n, "SparseLUSolve: P is corrupted");
10881  alglib.ap.assert(q[i]>=i && q[i]<n, "SparseLUSolve: Q is corrupted");
10882  }
10883  initreport(rep, _params);
10884  x = new double[n];
10885  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10886  {
10887  if( a.didx[i]==a.uidx[i] || a.vals[a.didx[i]]==0.0 )
10888  {
10889  rep.terminationtype = -3;
10890  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10891  {
10892  x[i] = 0;
10893  }
10894  return;
10895  }
10896  }
10897  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10898  {
10899  x[i] = b[i];
10900  }
10901  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
10902  {
10903  j = p[i];
10904  v = x[i];
10905  x[i] = x[j];
10906  x[j] = v;
10907  }
10908  sparse.sparsetrsv(a, false, true, 0, x, _params);
10909  sparse.sparsetrsv(a, true, false, 0, x, _params);
10910  for(i=n-1; i>=0; i--)
10911  {
10912  j = q[i];
10913  v = x[i];
10914  x[i] = x[j];
10915  x[j] = v;
10916  }
10917  rep.terminationtype = 1;
10918  }
10919 
10920 
10921  /*************************************************************************
10922  Reset report fields
10923 
10924  -- ALGLIB --
10925  Copyright 26.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
10926  *************************************************************************/
10927  private static void initreport(sparsesolverreport rep,
10928  alglib.xparams _params)
10929  {
10930  rep.terminationtype = 0;
10931  }
